People are continuously faced with social interactions throughout our day-to-day lives. Thus, we subconsciously practice the front stage theory and the looking glass theory. The front stage theory is a facade, or a performance, that people put on when surrounded by new people. The looking glass theory is how we think others feel about ourselves. Although the front stage and looking glass theory are comparable in that they both focus on how people view us in social interactions they differ in the ways that we alter our personalities in given situations. 
The front stage theory is a social space, created by Goffman, that provides a framework for understanding the many layers of identity presentation and social interaction. When participating in the front stage theory, representation of the public persona is created when faced with social situations. In doing so, they carefully choose their actions and appearances to leave the right impressions based on the audience. For example, when meeting someone for the first time you’re not as vulnerable due to the pressure of people watching your every move. The performance aspect of social interactions is emphasized heavily in Goffman's theory, which highlights how people intentionally control how they appear in different social contexts.
The Looking Glass theory compares to the front stage theory because of the idea that you are constantly putting on a performance to have a reaction from others. I have experienced these theories during Fall Recruitment for a sorority. As I was going around to different houses, I was constantly using my front stage self to be liked by different girls in each chapter. I projected my own image onto other people, in hopes that they might reflect it back to me. In addition, I experienced the looking glass theory when conversation flowed naturally because I felt as if the different girls, I talked to enjoy my presence. The dynamic interaction between an individual's internal self-concept and outside social cues is made clear by Cooley's theory. Cooley clarifies how people negotiate the challenging terrain of identity development among a network of social influences by highlighting the significance of social interactions and interpersonal perceptions. This viewpoint emphasizes the significant influence of social dynamics on a person's self-concept, underscoring the significance of empathy and understanding the formation of identity.
In contrast, these two theories go against each other because the front stage theory deals with how you individually alter your personality towards a certain group of people, whereas the looking glass self is focused on how you alter your personality based upon how others perceive you. For example, I enjoy eating capers on my pasta. When practicing the front stage theory, I would choose to eat something else when I am around new people. However, if I practiced the looking glass theory, I would choose to eat the capers on my pasta around new people, but I would be constantly second guessing myself and assuming the people I am with are judging me. 
As a result, during interpersonal interactions, the constant conversation between one's internal self-perception and outside social feedback produces an awareness and understanding of identity. Essentially, Cooley's theory stresses the passive reception and acceptance of social feedback in creating individual self-concept, whereas Goffman's theory emphasizes the active performance of self in social circumstances. Moreover, people actively build their social image to negotiate a variety of social circumstances, whether it is through the planned performances in Goffman's framework or the imagined reflections in Cooley's theory. When combined, these divergent viewpoints provide complicated insights on the intricate relationship between social impact and human agency in social environments and the complicated and diverse nature of identity formation. In contrast, Cooley's theory highlights the passive reception and internalization of social input in shaping individual self-concept, but Goffman’s theory highlights an individual change for approval of others. This view emphasizes the reciprocal nature of social interaction and the importance of social dynamics in forming identity formation.

Comparing Sociologists
In The Neurology of Religion, Maryanski and Turner argue that emotions are the simplest and purest form of the human consciousness. They emphasize the importance of emotions for the expansion of the process of acquiring knowledge and understanding it through thought, experiences, and/or the senses for ancestral hominids. This was accomplished by many points of evolution in the brain; this is to say that the brain did not undergo a sudden dramatic change. Rather, more and more connections between different areas of the brain started developing. They say the use of emotion enhances memory, for example a hominid finds two trees one has sweet delicious fruit in it, the other shoots seeds out of the trunk when it is touched protecting the fruit. The hominid would associate the two trees with emotions. The hominid could obtain the yummy fruit from one tree and would associate this tree with happiness. The other tree that shoots seeds out would be associated with pain, and fear, thus initiating memory for the hominid to know which tree to climb. With the introduction of memory came the  introduction to rationality, helping us make decisions based on thoughts we incorporate with choices often based on the memory. Emotion leads to these behavioral accomplishments and is the most basic concept that makes them up. Whether Harari read Maryanski and Turner’s work or not he shares this common idea and compliments their work with his own.
It is because Harari believes emotions to be fragile, pure, and basic that he believes they are able to be so easily manipulated and even broken or coded. Harari wants to warn the world of relying too heavily on technology as he is afraid of a future where an AI will dominate humans. To attain this an AI would need to have emotions, as we have discussed emotions lead to all sorts of more complex feelings and behaviors. It is also true that emotions lead to the feeling of superiority over lesser things. Humans consider themselves the superior species due to a greater grasp of emotions as it is embedded in the neurological working used to build a far more advanced society than any other animal. So who is to say if an AI were to grasp emotions that they would not get a sense of superiority to humans eventually. There are already cases where humans are inferior to AI’s. Harari even gives the example of chess, “A closer look at the world of chess might indicate where things are heading in the long run. It is true that for several years after Deep Blue defeated Kasparov, human-computer cooperation flourished in chess. Yet in recent years computers have become so good at playing chess that their human collaborators have lost their value and might soon become utterly irrelevant” (Harari, 2019, 32). This is a great example because it provides a good perspective as to how fast computers are learning the game that Harari defines as “one of the crowning glories of human intelligence” (2019, 33). In other words chess was considered a superior way of testing human intelligence and now computers are exponentially gaining on them. As a matter of fact, a new AI produced by Google called AlphaZero was able to overtake the leading chess algorithm in only four hours. It is now unclear if any human will ever be able to reign supreme in chess again. 
Harari fears giving AI emotions regardless of the fact that emotions are needed in order for an AI to help humans because an AI needs to value human life. Emotions would be the logical next step in the evolution of machines. If we want a machine to be able to unlock more complex functions such as the human brain, emotion is a vital step for that goal assuming an AI will process emotion the same way as the human brain. To code emotion into an algorithm is essentially the same as manipulating human emotion, Harari demonstrates how easy that task is with an example of musical arts in modern popularity. “Of course, personalized art might never catch on, because people will continue to prefer common hits that everybody likes. How can you dance or sing together to a song nobody besides you knows?  But algorithms could prove even more adept at producing global  hits than personalized rarities. By using massive biometric databases garnered  from millions of people, the algorithm could know which biochemical buttons to press in order to produce a global hit that would get everyone swinging like crazy on the dance floors. If art is really about inspiring (or manipulating) human emotions, few if any human musicians will be able to compete with such an algorithm, because they cannot match it in understanding the chief instrument they are playing on: the human biochemical system” (Harari, 2019, 29). This excerpt shows how easy and common it is to manipulate emotions. Despite Harari, and The Neurology of Religion having completely different topics,  Harari was still able to complement the work with aspects of his own. On the other hand,  Harari found an aspect of Maryanski and Turner’s work to be wrong in his opinion and disagreed with it.
The point of disagreement Harari has with Maryanski and Turner’s work is their view of religion and the role it plays in society. To understand the role of religion we first have to look at how religion was formed through human evolution. As we have already discussed, through the development of emotions humans started to become neurologically superior to other species which led to a greater social divide between humans and other species. For example,  humans have to perform work to maintain their social connections; this is due to the sheer emotional depth in interactions. Simply put, everything has meaning to humans in our interactions whether that meaning has a negative or positive connotation. Other mammals have bio programmers, automatic connections that can be thought of as their animalistic instincts. An elephant doesn’t have to learn to stick with the herd, it is sort of a natural law that mammals have to stay socially active. Whereas humans, while some find comfort in social situations, are a less socially dependent species.  It is seen as normal for an adult human to have a house of their own and not seek a family. It is their personal choice. Furthermore,  humans have become more intellectual because our emotional depth has developed. We are able to feel the weight of a decision and how it might affect not just ourselves but others as well. As we became more emotional we began to paint materialistic things with different emotional significance. This gave a greater importance to different objects, family heirlooms, ancestral artifacts, etcetera. As time passed on these objects that were held dear, protected, and made into tall-tales they became religious. They took an objective truth and through time these objects and the stories with them became fact.  Maryanski and Turner say that religion became an absolute truth for humanity and if we look back in history a lot of major policy decisions were made from religious persuasion. Maryanski and Turner praise the formation of emotions for being the keystone in human development that sparked the making of a far more complex society. They believe emotions will and should be the driving force behind important decision making. Furthermore, if religious decision persuasion is a byproduct of emotional thinking then Maryanski and Turner would be supporters. This is where the disagreement between Harari and the other authors comes. Perhaps it was acceptable in the past however for the 21st century Harari feels that religion should ultimately play a different role in policy making.
 The different roll should be not one at all. Harari covers this in one of his chapters in his book where he explains why he believes religion should have little to no role in policy making. Harari’s reasoning for this varies from religious ideals being outdated for modern society to religious influence having their religious motives above their intentions. Touching on outdated ideals Harai provides the example, “When Ayatollah Khamenei needs to make a crucial decision about the iranian economy, he will not be able to find the necessary answer in the Quran, because seventh century Arabs knew very little about the problems and opportunities of modern industrial economies and global financial markets. So he, or his aides must turn to Karl Marx, Milton Freedman, Frederick Hayek, and the modern science of economics to get answers” (Harari, 2019, 133-134). This perspective is that a lot of religious ideals were founded to solve olden problems and often times do not fit today's issues hence we cannot rely on religion to solve political issues as today we are facing issues unheard of  in the past. Harari suggests that religious scriptures can be used to justify modern solutions; however, when faced with a modern policy issue it would be very difficult to find a direct answer in scriptures. He suggests it is significantly easier to seek an answer outside of scripture and to then go back, find common ideas and twist the scripture to justify your answer claiming that you seeked the answer through religious means. Harari says “twisting the scripture degrades it, “from a source of true knowledge to a source of mere authority” (Harari, 2019, 134). Religious influence is a powerful thing, followers will whole-heartedly support the actions of their religious movement just because the leader of the movement is of their religion. This is to say that in America if two candidates were running for office and despite the opponent being more qualified Christians would still likely vote for the less qualified candidate simply because he is of their religion and his actions will reflect that of Christian ideals. Harari touches on this himself when he talks about the Pope leading a holy mission against global warming, because he is the highest Catholic leader. Catholics will support this movement while evangelicals will oppose it simply because he is Catholic. Harari states, “This is already beginning to happen. Opposition to environmental regulations is incorporated into the fire-and-brimstone sermons of some American evangelical pastors, while Pope Francis is leading the charge against global warming in the name of Christ… So perhaps by 2070, the environmental question will make all the difference in the world whether you are evangelical or Catholic. It goes without saying that evangelicals will object to any cap on carbon-emissions, while Catholics will believe that Jesus preached that we must protect the environment” (2019, 136). Harai even says that this will reflect in other areas such as the cars each side of the conflict will drive whether gasoline powered or electric cars. The influence of religion can be a dangerous thing, if  an idea turns into a religious dogma  there is  instantly a significant following because leaders will preach that the religious icon believed in it as well. Not only is this disrespectful to authentic scripture that is being mis-purposed but it is also creating a possible dangerous power struggle. Harari ultimately feels that it would be best if religious intentions and ideas were left out of major policy making.
Through Harari, Maryanski and Turner’s work we were able to see the way sociologists relate to each other’s work. It is clear that both sides were discussing completely different things. With Maryanski and Turner talking about the evolution and development of the modern human and Harari talking about where the 21st century will take us and how to prepare for it. Despite this sociologists always relate to one another whether by disagreeing or agreeing. This actually builds a stronger argument as it shows they are capable of comprehending other’s work and using that to further push thier own point.

A small overlook on Sociology’s many concepts
As we have all read what Harari had to say within his book “21 Lessons for the 21st Century” as well as the numerous readings within the many modules throughout our time in this Sociology class. There have been numerous points made that I am sure I was not the only one who were intrigued to learn about but with that comes some gray area. While we have read the brilliant concepts from authors including Durkheim, Mead, Goffman, Foucault, Harari and the list just goes on and on, it would be inadequate to say that there is no overlap in some of these concepts. Now rather that overlap be inconsistent or consistent with one another would be hard to tell with just a single glance at this material.
The first reading that I would like to bring to your attention is one of the first readings if not the very first one we were given, The Neurology of Religion which was written by Maryanski and Turner. This reading goes into quite some detail about the adaptions that had to happen for humans to reach the spot where they are today. Great Apes back in the early ages adapted in ways that seem far beyond understandable to me. These Great Apes were able to have rationality which only came about according to Maryanski and Turner because they had the ability to have emotions. When one is able to have emotions or has emotions in general it can allow for things such as stronger relationship bonds to form which would be needed for these Great Apes to eventually became the humans they adapted to. Emotions also enable one to think symbolically which when you look at the bigger picture this is what ultimately allowed societies, religions, and families etc. to be able to exist today. This then becomes quite consistent with the theory of collective consciousness (Durkheim) as a whole. 
With the Great Apes now not only being able to symbolically think as well as form these stronger bonds it will only continue to increase the size of one’s emotional capacity which made it possible for spoken languages as well as cultures to come about. As a part of all of this comes religion, and according to Durkheim society would not have to about if it wasn’t for religious forces. The belief that there is something beyond the life we lie here on Earth. This can be quite scary to think about especially since there is no evidence that there is anything after death for all we know it could be total darkness or we could all come back as bunnies…just something to think about! 
Back on the topic, religion gives something to the collective to believe in so the inevitable fate that awaits us all isn’t as scary. Harari on the other hand believes that while religion can help bring people together as well as give people what seems to be a sense of identity it also makes those who have different beliefs not be able to see eye to eye, which in all honesty is the truth in my opinion. Religion (chapter 8) according to Harari might not cure the many diseases that infect this world or build the bombs that we use/used in many wars, but religion does decide who you are and how you see others around you. It decides if you see someone like you generally see yourself or if you see them as the “other.” Religion has taken how many perceive people within the world to a whole new level. He expresses this by saying that there are “beautiful” religious traditions as well as there being “ugly” religious traditions. He then goes into detail talking about how these religious traditions divide people and that though we are all the same there are these “small differences” that determine how one will be treated. An example he gives of this would be how LGBT people are faced with what is ultimately a life-or-death situation depending on where they live. In Iran I don’t know if it is considered illegal to be gay and/or lesbian within the country but it is not rare for someone to be killed or most of the time they would be maltreated due to that fact that they liked the same sex as them. 
While both of these concepts of religion talk about how it shapes us in many ways, one can see the obvious difference between the two. Durkheim focuses on how religion shaped us into who we are and how it brought us together and allowed us to think symbolically and become the humans we are today. Harari focused his concept on how religion is what is ultimately tearing us apart. How religion today has it’s negative as well as positive impacts but the negative in my opinion outweighs what these positives are especially since nobody truly knows which religion is the most accurate and there is a good chance that we may never know seeing how it is tearing many of us apart and causing wars. These are kind of similar in the sense that they both build off of each other that while we needed religion to build us together it is also the thing that could break us apart.
Now the next reading I would like to bring light to is “Micro-foundations” by Fligstein and Macadam’s. Within this reading they both talked about how many humans thrive to have a purpose within their lives. This is similar to Durkheim’s theory that religion is really made so that we can avoid this “existential fear” because though it may not have anything to do with religion having a sense of purpose for your life can make the inevitable death, we all know a little too well a bit easier to bear. One goes through the same process of being confused and they may feel as though their life is ultimately meaningless whereas coming together as a collective and having these jobs can help them avoid that situation as a whole. Even if you take away the outlook on without jobs there would be no purpose or that life would not be as valued as it should be, our daily interactions with other humans continuously make us feel loved. Spending time with those around you regardless of if they are strangers give everyone a sense that they are not alone especially if it is during a bad situation.
Harari on the other hand in the chapter called “Work” discusses the topic that there is a decent chance that the workforce we have in our head in a few years may not be anything like we would think. These AI machines are beating humans at their own jobs which obviously would make sense being that they have algorithms and can learn things a lot faster than any human can. These algorithms could grant these private companies as well as the owners with more money and things that will enrich them even more. So, if the rich continue to only get richer than the poor will ultimately since their economic value will decrease as well as their political power. Also, since these machines will be getting to know you almost more than you know yourself it can allow for these companies to not only manipulate you but also make decisions for you. If this becomes the case, we will end up relying on them more than ever and it will become harder to stray away from these things. 
Though not having a job would not be the best thing in the world it would be beneficial when you are looking at the bigger picture. Having these AI’s take over some of these jobs could lead to improvements as well as better results in total. An example of this could be where Harari discussed the AIs would take over some of the doctors’ jobs which could help with new treatments and things of that nature to be known throughout the whole world within minutes since all the AI’s will be programmed the same. 
According to Harari when changing to robots doing majority of the work there will be dangers with algorithms. When you put these robots on the same system though it can help in a numerous number of ways there is also the chance that there will be mistakes but when all these machines are on the same system every one of them will make the mistake which can ultimately lead to some catastrophic results. Say the future did hold what Harari used as his topic for the chapter called “Work,” and we take it back to the example of the doctors and hospital staff being replaced with these programmed robots. Personally, I would find it quite terrifying to be about to undergo surgery and all I see is a robot there to comfort me knowing that there is even the slightest possibility that I may not make it out alive of that operating room. Regardless of the jobs being lost nothing can compare to the soothing aura of a nice man or lady being there and reassuring you that everything will be alright. I would be exactly like Fligstein and MacAdam’s said… I would feel meaningless that one I already don’t have a job so my life purpose that I worked hard for my whole life is thrown out the window but I also would feel terrified that I may get to experience the inevitable fate everyone is waiting for because the robot messed up an algorithm and now I am dead. With all of this being out in the open and knowing that Fligstein and MacAdam’s has a theory on how we as humans ultimately need a purpose in life it does leave one wondering what the future has in store for all of us.

Personal Monetization
The pervasive commercialization of personal relationships has proliferated in today's consumer-driven society. In the present-day era, people engage with others to acquire various benefits such as social recognition, financial gain, or emotional backing from them. To scrutinize this trend and examine its impact on our communal lifestyle through Erving Goffman's concept of "impression management," is a major objective for this document. This essay proposes that impression management tactics have become increasingly popular approaches utilized by individuals seeking advantages amidst the commodification of interpersonal connections within contemporary consumer-led societies.
Social interactions that are turned into commodities, where people act in a way to acquire social advantage or profit has been on the rise lately. Such behavior allows individuals to display themselves as appealing and is referred to as impression management - displaying oneself selectively so they can get desired reactions from others. Erving Goffman developed this concept when he theorized about social interaction, emphasizing its symbolic context with participants fully aware of their actions' significance and how others might perceive them.
There exist numerous instances that provide evidence for the notion of impression management. One such instance is the "Instagram influencer" trend, where individuals upload sanitized and glorified versions of themselves to their audience's delight. Instagram influencers meticulously select hashtags, filters, as well as lighting in order to portray an expert image of themself. By generating content that captivates both visually and intellectually, they are capable of drawing attention from a vast social media audience.
To delve deeper into the effects of commercialized personal connections on our society, it is noteworthy to analyze technology's function. The upsurge in social media and other technological developments have enabled us to maintain perpetual communication with others which wasn't always possible before; however, this comes with both favorable and unfavorable outcomes for our social existence. The favorability within this interconnectivity comes from the practically instantaneous communication it provides, yet this has created a culture of desensitization and overstimulation within the youth of the technological age. 
Looking at it from a different perspective, enhancements in technological innovations have enabled flawless interaction with people located all over the world despite their geographical whereabouts. This has presented novel avenues for social engagement and enabled us to cultivate meaningful bonds despite differences in culture or background. However, conversely speaking, the perpetual obligation to portray an ideal image on online platforms can be overwhelmingly taxing leading to a potential disposition towards unease and inner hesitation.
Moreover, the strides made in technology have paved fresh pathways for people to generate revenue from their interpersonal relationships. To exemplify, those who hold sway on social media platforms can take advantage of opportunities and accumulate a substantial sum by endorsing various commodities and amenities among their supporters. This has generated an innovative kind of career that capitalizes upon people's private connections enabling them to procure livelihoods through it.
Nevertheless, this conveys an inquiry regarding the veracity of these individual associations. Could a bona fide affiliation with someone exist if they are remunerated to endorse their merchandise? This is a multifaceted matter that necessitates further investigation; nonetheless, it emphasizes the plausible detriments when personal alliances become commoditized.
In its entirety, the commercialization of human affiliations is an intricate occurrence that manifests both favorable and undesirable consequences for our communal existence. Through investigating the significance of presenting oneself in a positive light and technology as influential factors, we can commence comprehending this tendency's influence while devising tactics to establish genuine and substantial bonds with one another.
An additional example is the method wherein individuals who are in committed bonds frequently utilize methods of deceit to display themselves as "the ideal duo" on their various social media profiles. This strategic portrayal, meant to elicit acknowledgement from others who similarly compare relationships through these displays, allows such pairs of people to exploit personal connections. This is similar to other aspects of our existence which can be commercialized under pressure for superior perfection and validation.
In today's age of commodified personal interactions, individuals are compelled to exhibit themselves favorably in order to impress others. The presentation of oneself extends beyond the realm of social media and is evident across other social contexts as well. A prime example being job interviews where first impressions occupy a paramount position in securing employment opportunities for candidates. Impression management has therefore become indispensable amidst the proliferation of social media platforms like Twitter, Facebook, and LinkedIn alongside an acute emphasis on presentability while stepping out into public spaces - making it a critical aspect synonymous with contemporary societal living patterns.
In the field of mental health research, there is a particular domain that examines how commodified social interactions affect individuals. Research indicates that feelings of anxiety and depression may escalate due to constant pressure to project an optimistic front on social media while simultaneously comparing oneself with other people's seemingly perfect lives. Consequently, personal connections can become commercialized in ways where competition for acceptance becomes necessary and online presence has to be monitored incessantly - leading towards heightened stress levels and loss of positive emotional experiences.
One of the consequences that arise from commodified personal connections is the likelihood for social disparity. Those who possess a talent for presenting themselves positively and accumulating more approval may be granted better access to resources and prospects. Take, for instance, well-known figures on various online platforms with an extensive fanbase; they can readily convert their popularity into sponsorships or endorsements - unlike those without much following whatsoever, as such individuals may miss out on these opportunities in its entirety. Consequently, creating a gap where people who adeptly commercialize their personal ties stand to profit while others are left at a disadvantage.
The commercialization of interpersonal connections could potentially have an adverse effect on our perception of sincerity and bona fide human interactions. In scenarios where social exchanges are motivated by self-interest, there may be reduced opportunities for genuine dialogue or emotional intimacy. People might feel compelled to portray themselves in a particular manner to earn acceptance or evade criticism, thereby resulting in less sincere communication and superficial bonds between individuals.
Considering the potential ramifications that may ensue, it is imperative to contemplate on our approach towards social interactions and what motivates us to pursue them. While the inclination to capitalize on personal relationships could stem from present-day consumerism, taking a proactive stance against this tendency becomes our responsibility as individuals. Our priority should always be cultivating sincere human connections without any ulterior motives in mind rather than prioritizing private benefits over them. By accentuating building genuine bonds and esteeming connection beyond societal standing, we yield an opportunity for more gratifying social lifestyles that are imbued with significance.
As we come to an end of this paper, it is important that we reflect on the commercialization of personal connections in modern-day consumer-oriented societies by making use of Erving Goffman's theory on social conduct. The exchange or selling of such links has resulted in individuals purposely presenting themselves favorably before others. This analysis demonstrates how impression management has become a critical tool for achieving benefits such as positive feedback from society, emotional support and material wealth within current day societal set-ups. Nonetheless, further research must be carried out to fully understand the impact associated with commodified interpersonal interactions.

The Looking Glass Self
What does it mean to see yourself through someone else’s perspective? A question that many people ponder upon. Along with everyone else I was in search for an answer. Why was it that my view of myself changes when I am around certain people? It has been believed that this could be because your self-esteem has gotten lower, or you just have the wrong friends, which could potentially all feed into the answer.
The looking glass self, a concept created by Charles Horton Cooley, is what effects how one may feel about themselves. Just like how one may see their peers around them it is most likely completely different from how they believe they are. Perspective and perception play a huge role within the way anyone views themselves. Cooley states within the looking glass self that it is ultimately the way we see ourselves socially, it is our social self.
Throughout my eighteen years of living, I have encountered numerous amounts of people from a variety of different backgrounds. When meeting these people, it came to my attention that there were always certain people I would much rather be around, and they all have something in common. Anyone who has ever approached me with good energy or just seemed like they were happy to be in the same place I was made me feel as if I belonged. They showed no negativity towards me so I knew that they couldn’t have seen me in a negative manner.
To get a little more in depth there was a time back in the summer of 2017 where I went to Europe. I got to see four beautiful places, London, Paris, Brussels, and Amsterdam though I had an amazing experience overseas and I would love nothing more to go again there were some things that made me see myself differently while being there. Obviously, going to a completely different continent would mean that I was also going to experience different cultures as well as different people. One of the days I was there I was in the airport at London and a woman continuously kept watching me and just looking at me as if she were confused. She then decided to come up to me and ask me if I was Norwegian, I told her that I was not, but she was more than convinced that I was someone from Norway. I have never been asked something like that before probably because some people believe it is rude to ask, “what are you?” but it opened a door for me and started to make me question whether people see me and assume that I am from a certain ethnic group and/or race. It then opened my imagination up to the idea that some people might assume I belong to a said race or ethnic group and judge me poorly from it. It messed with my mind for a while and still sometimes does. This woman also then continuously wanted to hear me speak because I sounded like I “was from Texas” and she had never seen a girl who looked the way I did speak the way that I do. This then led me to think I sound absolutely ridiculous and that everyone probably agreed with her because my voice really doesn’t match my looks.
I have also had many friends within my life to which I have made some crazy memories with but there are barely a handful that make me feel good about myself. The way that they all look at me and care for me like no one else has and always come to me with open arms and big smile on their face shows me that they have no intentions other than pure ones. They make me feel like my authentic self when I am around them and from the way they continuously act they show me that I am worth so much and that I am valued. They came along after I hit a hard place in my life. A guy that I saw the world of and who I at first thought saw the same of me really changed how I saw myself. He treated me as if I had no purpose in my life and as if I did something so horrible to hurt him. After being around someone who treats you in a negative manner for so long it takes a toll on how you see yourself. I started to believe that no matter what I did nothing I would ever do would be right. He made me believe by the way he treated me that I did not deserve to be loved and that my worth amounted to absolutely nothing. This then led to me feeling like everyone perceived me the way I perceived myself at that time which made me feel even worse about myself. I assumed everyone had lost hope for me just as I had lost hope for myself because a man who had no idea what he was doing with his life treated me so badly that I figured it must’ve been the way that I was that caused this. It wasn’t until I met my friends that I mentioned before that changed how I perceive myself and how I assume others perceive me. 
Charles Horton Cooley believes that there are these “three principal elements” that tend to create what he calls “the looking glass self” they are the imagination of how we believe another person sees us, the imagination of the judgement that we think comes along with their perception of us, and then the feeling we then get from those things which can range from prideful and happy to worthless and depressed. The concept itself is about how we view our self-image which can be greatly influenced by the interactions we make with people around us and by what society deems as acceptable. 
An example of this concept could look a little something like this. I am going to meet up with some people within a club I have recently joined. I personally think I am a very friendly person and are quite easy to talk to so I can hold a conversation though I am nervous about going to meet these new people I trust that my social skills can potentially help me avoid any type of awkwardness and spark a connection with some of these people. I get there and I am trying to make casual conversation, so everyone isn’t sitting there looking bored or in all just ready to leave. In response to trying to break the ice the only responses I seem to get are either very short sentences, or no response at all. Everyone avoids really keeping eye contact which I find is a key piece to making conversation and showing interest. I then begin to feel anxious because I believed in my social skills but now it is seemingly like they are currently failing me. Whereas if these new people I would’ve met would have held eye contact as well as try to carry on the conversation my views on my social abilities would not have changed. Depending on if a positive response would have been given, I would still have faith in my abilities and the self-image I have for myself would have remained the same. Since all I received was a majority of negative responses rather than be words or just body language it then led me to see myself differently and feel as if they wanted nothing to do with me when we met, and it seemed as if they did not even want to have a conversation with me in the first place.
With the knowledge you now have about the looking glass self we can now relate them back to the experiences I spoke on before. When in the London airport I went in assuming by the looks of me as well as how I acted that one would be able to view myself for what I was. I am a biracial female who is half African American as well as Caucasian. When I was approached by this woman of a race and/or ethnic group I wasn’t sure of and was asked whether I was Norwegian it nonetheless confused me. In her eyes I was of Norwegian descent, but I was nowhere near being that. It then made me believe that other people probably saw me for something I wasn’t as well. Then when she commented on my accent and how my voice did not match what she would’ve assumed I would have sounded like it really made my self-image change I become very self-conscious of how other people saw me because of the way my voice sounded. I thought to myself “do I sound like a country hillbilly to everyone?” which I have found out is true but that is irrelevant at this moment. In all hearing that my voice sounded like it belonged to someone quite different from me really affected me because from that moment forward, I felt like everyone thought I sounded crazy.
Looking back on the time that I was getting treated terribly and feeling like I didn’t deserve anything good to happen in my life I see now that I felt this way because that man was my “biggest mirror” he was who I cared about the most and would do anything under the sun for. I say he was my biggest mirror because he was what determined how I felt about myself and then it eventually went to how I thought everyone saw me. Getting treated rudely by one of the only people who truly understood you will make you question quite a few things. My “biggest mirror” within this looking glass concept was giving me the idea and really persuading me all together that I was the problem then I did become the problem because I allowed him to make me see things the way he wanted me to. 
What does it mean to see yourself through someone else’s perspective? The looking glass self is how one does so. You get around these people rather you just met them or if they have been in your life for a while but the way the interactions go, they place ideas in your head of how that person or those people perceive you. If you are continuously getting treated horrible by someone or the way, they give off body language is negative then that will lead to you having a negative look on yourself as well as feeling down as well. Now if you are continuously praised by these people and you are shown nothing less than their love for you this will make the idea you have of yourself take a positive turn. Surrounding yourself with people who are positive when interacting with you will enable you on your journey to have a better self-image. One is not defined by how others act towards you but it can often seem like it due to Cooley’s concept the looking glass self.

Thriving and Surviving
	Have you ever seen a woman working as an electrician?  How about a mechanical engineer?  The answer is probably yes being that it is the 21st century, however, that does not mean that women do not face the same discrimination that they faced decades ago just because of their gender.  Sometimes these women become subject to a concept called defensive othering, which is when they know that they are a part of a subordinate group, however, they believe that they are not a part those judgments and discriminations.  Although this now allows the one subordinate group to subjugate another, sometimes it is necessary to do so in a male dominated field just for a woman to thrive.  I have faced a similar situation being a woman who is a deckhand.  I understand from both sides what it is like to be discriminated against and what it is like to be a part of defensive othering.  In a field that is predominately male, sometimes it is crucial to do so.
	Women have come a long way when it comes to the careers they are able to pursue.  A job that we have begun to conquer is engineering.  Now more than ever there are woman engineers excelling in their field, but they still have a long way to go regarding the bias that they face.  Obviously, it was not so easy for them to get to where they are today.  Along with the massive amounts of education that they have to go through, they also had an extra step to take, which was persevering over the tremendous hurdles of everyone telling them that they will never make it as an engineer.  In the past, women always had to live up to the standard of being the beautiful housewife, who would cook, clean, and live for her husband.  It was not classified as normal to even have a job, let alone a job that was deemed as “manly”.  This made it so much harder for them to accomplish their goals.  Of course, these stereotypes and judgments can be ignored, but for how long until it becomes unbearable?  For my first year and a half of college, I was a coastal engineering major.  It was me and two other girls as the only females in my engineering classes.  Most of the time, we got the feeling that the guys thought that they were better than us, just because we are girls.  Eventually we learned that we had to join the mentality that they had just so we did not feel subordinate to them.  Although it was contradicting in that it was going against feminism, it is what we had to do to thrive in our male dominated classes.  Not only did we stop feeling inferior to the men in the class, but we also saw improvements in our grades.  It is necessary to adapt to the environment that you are in so that you can succeed.
	The same concept occurred at my job.  At home, I am a deckhand on a ferry boat, and I started when I was 16.  Not only was I discriminated against by some of the passengers, but also by my male colleagues.  Through the years, I have heard things like, “Give that to him, it’s too heavy for you to lift” or “Why is there a little girl running the boat? Where is the captain, I do not feel safe”.  These are comments that both my female colleagues and I hear constantly from passengers, and we know by now that it is something that is going to be difficult to get around.  On the other hand, we quickly figured out a way to fit in with our male coworkers, while still being able to adhere to being feminine.  Although it may not be something that we are proud of, defensive othering is what has helped us develop our confidence and flourish at our jobs.  Another part of the company is the job of the ticket girls.  The ticket girls tend to be more girly and feminine than the girls who are deckhands.  They also have fewer and less vigorous tasks as ticket girls.  A way in which us female deckhands use defensive othering is by comparing ourselves to the ticket girls.  By creating a sense that we accomplish more, and have more demanding tasks, we have found that the men at our job will not see us as equal to the ticket girls but hold us at a higher standing because we are acting in a similar way to the men.  Again, it is not something to brag about, however, if it is not done then, it is tough for us to gain any confidence in what we are doing, which then makes it extremely difficult for any of us to move up in rank.
	The concept of defensive othering is not only seen in careers, but in many other places as well.  For example, in some sports that are deemed as “men’s sports”, the women that participate create a shield that protects them from being discriminated against.  The shield that they create is their attitude, which they modify to act like their oppressor.  These women believe that if they act like the “dominant class” which would be men, that they will not be subject to the bias that all women face.  For them to prove themselves to the dominated power, they need to reinforce that the stigmatizing labels, such as girls not being as strong or physically coordinated as men, are true of other women, but not for them.  Although the concept refutes many of the things that feminists have worked for, it is a coping mechanism that has helped groups that are subject to the stigmas.  It gives the group a sense of confidence that they would otherwise not have if it were not for this coping mechanism.  As controversial as this concept may appear, there are many situations in which it has helped people of subjugated groups thrive in an environment that in the past, would not even allow them in.
	Clearly, I can speak from experience when I say that I have become a member of defensive othering.  Being a deckhand, an engineering major, and a woman, I must find some way to succeed in places where men see themselves as superior.  It is a conflicting topic for me knowing that on some level, it is wrong because it reverses what feminists have worked their entire lives for, but on the other hand, it allows me to find my place in positions that I can feel superior and accomplished.  Being a part of a group that participates in defensive othering lets me to put myself in the shoes of other people that are in situations that are like mine.  It is now evident that minorities partake in this behavior as a coping mechanism.
	Sometimes, there are situations where it is necessary to become a part of defensive othering.  It becomes a mechanism to thrive and survive in places that have a clear dominant group.  Many people have already discovered that this is the case because they feel inferior to the so-called dominant group, based on stigmas that developed from the past.  Although it is morally wrong in some cases, people need to find ways in which they can succeed in the areas in which they feel they are the minority.

The Impacts of Socioeconomic Differences on Maternal Healthcare
	Rural areas are infamous for lacking resources in departments such as education, healthcare, and transportation in comparison to urban areas. This phenomenon is commonly due to a lack of money in these areas.  As countries develop, one might assume that those living in poorer parts of the country would receive more money and better services. However, that rarely happens. So, what happens to the mothers who have no or limited maternal healthcare? How does that affect the child’s health and its chance of survival? How is the mother’s physical and mental health affected? Socioeconomic differences cause women to receive varying levels of healthcare, and studies have shown that women in rural, impoverished, or uneducated areas are more likely to receive inferior care. In this paper, I will discuss the effects socioeconomic differences have on the mother’s physical and mental health, infant mortality rate, and infant injury and explain why all mothers should receive equal healthcare. 
	Socioeconomic differences in maternal health care align with the unit in class regarding race and oppression, specifically Collins’s The Matrix of Domination. In this work, she presents the idea that all women are discriminated against in comparison to men solely because of their gender. From this, one can imply that women do not receive quality maternal healthcare as it is not a service that men require. The healthcare quality one receives is based on institutional biases such as race, class, and gender. According to Collins, black women are the most disadvantaged in society as they are discriminated against due to their race, gender, and sex, which all intersect to form a matrix of discrimination. Collins also states that the world’s Eurocentric view causes society to see people as two races- black or white- meaning that any woman who is not white is considered black. This issue is significant as women of color tend to also be in lower social classes, challenging them with more socioeconomic struggle. These struggles include education, access to resources, family size, and workplace occupations, which all impact their health. 
	Some countries, such as New Zealand, have maternity care that is government-funded and free for all women (Dawson et al., 2021). The system is composed mostly of midwives. However, women do have the option to pay to see specialists, such as an obstetrician. Despite all women having free access to maternal healthcare, there are still inequalities. Approximately 3,800 women in New Zealand voluntarily completed a survey regarding their health care experience with additional data detailing their residential locations. The results showed that transport, housing, poverty, racism, and lower education levels were all barriers to equitable health and the outcome of the mother and the baby. The most vulnerable groups of women tended to be the most unsatisfied as younger, highly deprived, and remote rural women were most affected by inequality. They had fewer accessible services as healthcare centers were distributed based on population. Additionally, they had difficulties getting transportation to better facilities in urban areas. Women identifying as Pacific or Māori had more struggles as they said that cost was a factor in obtaining maternity care other than the standard midwife appointments, such as antenatal care (Dawson et al., 2021). 
	New Zealand has a better maternity healthcare model than most developed countries. For example, in the US, maternal healthcare is not provided to all women and is far from free. However, there are still issues with New Zealand’s healthcare system. The lack of quality services given to women in areas with less economic resources is an issue as a zip code should not determine healthcare. Health is a human right and should not be taken from someone due to circumstances out of their control, such as the availability of health centers near them. This is especially true as public transportation is often not provided to women in rural areas. Additionally, one's money should not dictate their health, but even in New Zealand, money became a factor. Women in more urban areas with more clinics available, also tended to have more money (Dawson et al., 2020). This meant that if they had pregnancy complications, they had access to and were able to pay to see a specialist (Dawson et al., 2021). That implies that women with more money have more of a right to be healthy, receive more care,  and have healthy babies.
	Socioeconomic differences in New Zealand caused mothers to be unsatisfied with their physical healthcare, and an Italian study showed socioeconomic differences also cause decreased mental healthcare (Cena et al., 2020). Perinatal depression (PND) is one of the most commonly seen pregnancy complications and is known to produce severe effects on both the mother’s mental health and the development of the fetus. This study examined factors of age, nationality, previous abortions, previous pregnancies, how many of the woman’s children were alive, if the woman planned the pregnancy, and if the woman had resources for reproductive technology. 1,471 women from eleven healthcare centers in Italy filled out a 10-question survey in addition to an unstructured clinical interview to study these factors. The study determined that PND was present in all socioeconomic groups. However, the women from whom it was their first pregnancy that also had at least temporary employment had a lower risk of PND. Conversely, the risk of PND was highest in women with a lower education status and work or economic stressors. Similarly, postpartum depression (PPD) was found only in women who had several or severe economic problems (Cena et al., 2020). 
	The results of this study showed that women who had economic problems were most likely to have depression associated with their pregnancy (Cena et al., 2020). Not only did this put them at greater risk for PND, but socioeconomic disadvantages directly correlated to antenatal depression (AND) and PPD. Women who had not had already had children were more likely to have better mental health since they did not have the economic stressor of multiple children. Not only is this a problem for the mothers, but it is also a problem for their children, who can face decreased fetal development as a result (Cena et al., 2020). Once again, health should not be determined by where a person lives. Mental health disorders can affect people for years, and it is not right that people should have to suffer with them due to not having adequate care. 
	The effects of a mother's mental health on fetal development should not be overlooked, as, in 2019, 7.6 million children died before they reached the age of 5, 47% of which was due to neonatal mortality (Chauhan et al., 2021). Over half of those deaths were in developing countries. This was a direct result of the mothers not receiving proper maternal healthcare services, specifically antenatal care. Currently, the leading cause of neonatal mortality is antenatal, natal, or postnatal care, which practices such as vaccination and institutional deliveries could decrease. When researchers surveyed 6,01,509 households in India, results showed utilization of maternal healthcare varied greatly among socioeconomic regions based on antenatal care, safe delivery, and postnatal care. Women experiencing their first pregnancy in urban areas with access to mass media sources who did not work were the most likely to receive proper health care. These women were less likely to lose their children as a result of early neonatal mortality. Women that received early neonatal, postneonatal, and antenatal care were the most likely to have surviving children. This chance was not affected by demographic differences. However, socioeconomic differences were a significant factor in the children’s health. Uneducated women living in rural areas and with no exposure to the mass media experienced higher rates of early neonatal mortality. However, they still fared better than mothers in scheduled castes or scheduled tribes with very little access to healthcare  (Chauhan et al., 2021).
	This study showed that the use of maternal healthcare services severely affects the chances of early neonatal, neonatal, and post-neonatal mortality  (Chauhan et al., 2021). The use of these services is in turn affected by socioeconomic features such as location and economic status. Women with a lower socioeconomic status received less and lower quality healthcare. This directly correlated to a higher chance of infant mortality. That correlation supports the idea that proper healthcare needs to be normalized everywhere. In the 20th century, women should not be losing children due to a lack of resources, especially due to predetermined circumstances. For instance, the women in scheduled castes and tribes are born into them  (Chauhan et al., 2021). They frequently have no chance to leave, and even if they did, would not leave, as that is all they have known. However, that leads those women to have a much higher chance of losing their children. In a world where countries have the money to stockpile nuclear weapons continuously, there should be enough resources to prevent mothers from losing their families. 
	Socioeconomic groups greatly contribute to both infant mortality and injury.  In a study done in the UK, researchers studied brachial plexus (BP) injury in infants (Merrison et al., 2020). BP injury involves damage to the supraclavicular brachial plexus resulting in long-term self-image, mobility, and function issues. The study was conducted in the peripheral nerve unit of a hospital serving Northern Ireland, Wales, and South England. Researchers surveyed the participants through a questionnaire.  In the study, ethnicity data followed the categories used in the UK census. There was an increased risk of BP in patients who did not identify as white. Patients who classified themselves as Asians were 2.7 times more likely than whites to have a BP injury, and those considering themselves black were 6 times more likely than whites to suffer this injury. However, those weren’t the only groups affected by this injury. Except for Indians, all ethnic minority groups were at a higher risk than whites. Additionally, those from deprived areas were also at greater risk. While there were limits to the study, such as the self-reported questionnaire, language barriers, and a lack of a control population, the risk for BP correlated with several factors. These factors ultimately included biological factors, access to care, health education, inequity within healthcare, and language barriers (Merrison et al., 2020).
	This study showed that the healthcare system is very exclusive regarding race (Merrison et al., 2020). Women who were white and from an area with more resources were less likely to have a child with a BP injury. Additionally, BP injuries correlated with language barriers (Merrison et al., 2020). While it is difficult for a hospital to incorporate all languages, they should accommodate the major languages of their country, which this study showed is not the case. A woman’s ethnicity and native language should not stop her or her child from receiving adequate healthcare. This problem is significant in society today, since 13 years after researchers conducted the study, no one has made any changes to rectify the situation. 
	These four studies support Collins’s theory of Eurocentric thinking. The healthcare institutions provided white women with the healthiest babies, while women of color suffered. Since race, class, and gender all operate on the institutional level, women of color also face discrimination due to their class which is often associated with their race. Socioeconomic differences such as location, education level, and the previous number of abortions are all things that are frequently out of women’s control but still greatly affect their lives. The brachial-plexus injury study expressed surprise that in 13 years, women and their infants had not received better care. Collins would not be surprised by this as she theorized that social change would require a “changed consciousness of individuals and social transformations of political and economic institutions.” Women, especially those of lower class and color, have been oppressed since the beginning of society and will continue to be as underprivileged groups are in the same situations, allowing each group to gain a varied amount of privilege or punishment. So, even though all women are discriminated against, white women are unlikely to do anything about it as they are still treated better than women of color. Yet, health, a basic human right, should not be dictated by one’s zip code or the color of their skin.

From the Perspective of “Other”

Tap, Tap, tap… straighten posture, shift weight, keep eyes down, no, keep your eyes up, be confident, smile, look approachable. These are the many thoughts that circle a woman's mind while walking down the street. Billboards and magazines of the ideal woman's physique at every turn, unable to escape the perfection of the surrounding. Above the want for gentle eyes, silky hair, and radiant skin, there's one factor that far outweighs the desire of my appearance and want of the “male gaze.” The thought so frequently pops into my head of what it would be like to have the respect and stature as that of a man. Since the beginning of time, women have been dissimilar, supplementary and seen as “other” to the male sex. With no independent history, culture, or belief system, women have been in the shadow of man, supporting one's goals, aiding in their needs, and providing in any way achievable. 
Since coming to UNCW I have visited the Recreation Center an average of four days a week give or take. Wednesday, February 8th, 2023, I approached the Rec Center eager to start my workout. After completing my five sets on the leg press, I approached the young man on the squat rack and asked, “Hey man, how many sets do you have left?” He responds, “Oh, I just started a new workout, so four to five sets.” With a smile on my face, I answered, “Okay. May you please let me know when you’re done? Thank you!” After walking away, not two minutes go by, and the young man sees what I assume to be his friend and gives him the rack. Although a little shocked, and thrown off by this interaction, I brushed it off. I then approached the only other squat rack in the gym and proposed to the man the same question. After being looked at from head to toe, he informs me that he has two sets left. Walking away, I watch the same event transpire. Giving another man the rack, my jaw drops in disbelief. Staring at the situation before me, I was puzzled. Thinking of all the possible reasons why one would not allow another a simple request, I struggled to come to a single conclusion. A couple days went by, and I spoke to one of my male friends that lives in my dorm, who also actively attends the gym. That’s when it hit me. I questioned, “How do I earn the respect of a man?” His head tilted abruptly, paused for a minute and mumbled, “I don’t know.” As a man who often makes jokes about gender differences whether that be “women can’t drive” or “women wear clothes for men, not for themselves,” he was not pleased with the treatment I was experiencing at the gym.
Raised in a divided home with a dominating father and a goal driven mother, I saw the many conflicts that not playing your “gender role” creates. My father informed me from a young age of a woman's role in society. The caretakers of the household and appeal to the man's eye. Since 2nd grade, I have desired a career in the medical field, specifically, a medical doctor.  These desires were constantly shot down as my father would say, “You shouldn’t become a doctor, you won’t have time for family, for your kids. Why not be a nurse?” He attempted to condition me to dress, speak, and portray myself as something to be advertised and admired by others. I can’t tell you the countless times I've heard, “that isn’t ladylike.” In comparison, my mother taught me that I am capable of anything permitting I put in the work… until I wanted to join the military, then all bets were off. Women that stray from their gender role and lack the desire to conform are put in undesirable positions in regard to relationships and profession. If surrounded in a male dominated environment, there will always be something to prove, because after all who wants the girl on their team. 
Simone de Beauvoir, writer, activist, and social theorist focuses many of her pieces on women, most notably, “Second Sex.” She voices how women are viewed in comparison to men and how naturally speaking women are the inferior sex and always have been. In 1949, Beauvoir explained women's place, when expressing, “They live dispersed among men tied by homes, work...to certain men-fathers or husbands-more closely than to other women ” (pg-261). As a tactic of control, men have kept women separate, focusing their attention to the kitchen, the house, and the children. Without any purpose independently, there is an attachment that is created that ensures that a woman would not survive without the economic stability of a man. Due to the lack of financial contribution, women have had to compensate with their appearance, cooking skills, and physical affection for a man. A woman's purpose has been to serve, whether that be their husbands or their fathers, but never themselves. Self-interest is a pleasure not given, as every other member in their household takes priority. In addition to that, on page 260, Simone quotes the famous Aristotle, “The female is female by virtue of a certain lack of qualities” (Woman as Other). In this section of the piece, Beauvoir quotes many respected men in their fields, all of them displaying women as something to be conquered, lesser, and defective. Right off the bat, women have been almost pitied for their ignorance and have played the role of the underdog for far too long. Without quality education, resources, and equal opportunity how would one expect a man and a woman to possess the same qualities, skills, and experiences at that time. Marilyn Frye had an excellent analogy for comparing oppression to a bird in a cage. Being caught in metal bars or wires, restricts one's ability to spread their wings and flourish.  No matter how many times one chirps or chitters, the barrier set in place by the bars allows the system (men) to observe with leisure, benefiting from the beauty, while the decoration remains trapped inside. 
As time has gone on and women have strayed from their household duties, there is a new problem underway. In an attempt to control women, there is a new war in place, women against women. Naomi Wolf provides insight on the new struggles women encounter when stating, “...attractive, successful working women, there is a secret “underlife” poisoning our freedom ; infused with notions of beauty… self-hatred, physical obsessions, terror of aging, and dread of lost control” (pg. 1). Every place you go there is an illustration of this in society. Women often speak of getting botox, liposuction, fake tans, and other aesthetic procedures. Girls in high school are even infected with this desire, as they chase the appearance and attention of the women they see on social media. The gossip of putting others down for their bodies, continues, as the standard of beauty increases. If you haven’t heard, the attraction scale has changed from the 1-10 rating to 1-30 to account for breasts, face, and derriere. Pornography has climbed to the top of the ladder for mainstream media. As women have begun to advance in society, attend college at higher rates than men, fight for higher level positions of power, one more factor of control had to be computed to once again seclude and create a barrier of division between women across the country, and the world. 
Through experience and evaluation of the society around me, I have come to realize that the concept of earning the respect of a man is unattainable. Upon seeing an individual, there are certain perceptible characteristics including age, race, and sex. Before a word even slips off one's tongue, perceptions have already been made based on their physical appearance and overall presentation.  Women around the world continue to feed into this perpetual sequence by upholding the standards of the beauty myth. Conforming to the expectations will forever yield the same undesirable results. Women often talk about how upsetting it is to be treated with such lack of kindness and respect by men but take it without refusals like they’ve been conditioned to. I too have played my own part in this debacle, however in recent times I have gained a deeper perspective regarding the identification of where these issues stem and the potential solutions to these problems. This pattern continues because the men and women in this society that are raising their children are doing a poor job of straying from the collective consciousness and the double standards held to each sex. My mother still tells me to not go out at night, still asks me if I have pepper spray on my keychain. My stepfather, a man's opinion I hold in high regard, told me that I should not step off campus alone, that I should bring a “friend”, but we all know when he said that he meant male friend. 
This is the problem of our generation and the generations before us. There is an undeniable power struggle of respect between men and women and mothers and fathers have aided in this neglect. Children are only as skilled as we give them space to be. Having different standards for your opposite sex children causes boys to think girls are not capable, not competent, and not trusted. That is why when a woman does something as well or better than a man, all eyes are on her. The beauty myth and expectation of performing one's role denies a woman her full potential. Discouragement from family, friends, and peers does not create a supporting environment to breed success. Whereas a man has been raised to believe he will accomplish great things and be an author of his own destiny. This superiority complex plays a role in our everyday interactions. Whether that be the classroom, grocery store, household, or the gym, one does not escape it. 
In addition to that, without respect for one's wishes and values held dear to them, consent has become a major dilemma of this parental and societal failure. Without the necessary backing from a young age, regarding the utility of men and women, the “other” sex has been exploited and made as a tool to serve man's sexual desires and cravings.  The thrill of the chase, the anticipation of the capture, this animal behavior has been tolerated for far too long. Regardless of the regulations that have been established in workplaces, women still face many issues of respect from their male coworkers, customers, and employers. What appears to be a never-ending cycle is in fact just another representation of the lack of respect across the country and the world for women as the “incidental” being.  A man should be equally afraid of a woman as he is a man, and a woman should know that she is capable of more than being just another pretty face. 
In conclusion, women have been thrown into a box of seclusion and limitation since the beginning of time. The expectations set in the Stone Age still hold true today and the generations to come will continue to encounter these issues of unbalanced respect. Without the change of the collective consciousness spread throughout society regarding the role of a man vs the role of a woman and parental standards, the fight of oppression will always be a losing battle. As the fight goes on, measurements will be taken to continue to control women whether that be their role, job opportunities, appearance, or the community within us. The ability and respect of an individual should not be determined by what is between their legs, but between their ears.

Gender in Today’s World
	Have you ever been outcasted because something that you liked was deemed too masculine or too feminine for you to like?  Many people face a time in their lives where this occurs.  Whether it be a boy that likes the color pink and to play with dolls or a girl who likes the color blue and to play football.  Society has created these ideas that each gender must follow an extremely rigid set of rules to be seen as “normal” within the society.  When someone does something outside of these rules people are hesitant to accept their actions because it has been ingrained in their minds that their actions are “wrong.”   Every day we unknowingly do things because of these societal set of rules.  When we alter our natural behavior to fit into what society deems acceptable, we are “doing gender.”   We are taught by society that there are specific actions and behaviors that we have that are directly related to our sex even though science has proven that there are not very many biological differences between males and females.  The perceptions of male and female that society has taught us since we were young enables us to be more skeptical to try things outside of the rules of our specific gender. 
	Despite the presence of gender roles and rules of masculinity and femininity, the world we live in today has been more progressive towards the idea that gender is socially constructed and can be done in different ways.  Society has become more welcoming to the idea of women working in male dominated fields and men fulfilling home duties which in the past were viewed as abnormal and strange.  People are more equipped to challenge the rules of gender because of the sociologic research done to prove the socially construction of gender.  When people start to realize gender is a social construct, it is much easier to question the sexist thoughts that we have been taught.  One is able to tell themselves that their perception of what is acceptable as a man, or a woman has only been constructed by society not science and that if they are to defy the gender norm they are not biologically or inherently different than their peers.  I am not trying to argue that our society has completely overcome the sexism that gender norms have inflicted, but I believe there has been significant progress in questioning gender norms.  Although gender roles/norms are still present in society today, there has been more acceptance with defying the rules of gender.
	In the past, the roles of men and women were very different than those of today.  We can see how far feminism and breaking gender roles has come since the late 1800s by looking at Charlotte Perkins Gilman’s article titled “The Yellow Wallpaper.”  In this article, Gilman describes a fictional experience of a woman going through a depressive episode.  She explains how her husband, who is a doctor that diagnosed her illness, has been dismissing all of her opinions and not allowing her to do the things she likes to do like writing.  The readers can tell that the husband is belittling her and has a dominance over her.  The woman in the story feels like she owes the husband because he has taken care of her and given her a house to live in, but she is also aware of how poorly he treats her and that it is not fair to her.  The readers start to get frustrated with the woman because they know she deserves to be treated better but she continues to make excuses for the husband.  Gilman wants her female readers to see that they are actually the woman in the story, and it is time to stand up for themselves.  She wants them to fight the gender rules that say that women are supposed to stay at home and are not supposed to do anything without the approval of a man.  During this time period, women were not viewed as equal citizens, but Gilman’s article was a very influential piece in helping women realize they deserve equality.  The gender rules during this time period were so rigid that they were embedded in the justice system.  Women did not have rights to own property or vote and were seen as objects in the eyes of the law, not people.  Defying the gender norms as a woman in this time period would be as simple as wanting to make your own decisions.  Women that did not want to be controlled by a man and did not get married would be outcasts in society.  They would often fail to be able to support themselves because the system was built to benefit the man, not the woman.  Fortunately, things are vastly different in today’s world due to the persistence and fight of the women before us.  Now, a woman owning her own house and making a livable income is possible and seen as something pretty normal.  The societal view as to what a woman can do has majorly shifted from the late 1800s to now. 
Women have come very far in gaining rights to work our way to being seen as equal to men, but there are still areas and environments where women are still seen as inferior and not belonging.
