After the initial hesitance to having a female in their class, the other boys in the class came to accept the idea that a girl could do well in the class.  I took this opportunity to enlighten the boys in my class and show them that girls can be strong and interested in weightlifting too.  Despite the original pushback from my classmates and teacher, I was still able to make strong relationships with the people in the class.  As the class went on, I got really close with the teacher and made some really close friends.  In this experience, I was able to see firsthand the hesitancy society has instilled in people to a person breaking gender norms, but I also saw that people are capable of overcoming their learned perceptions.  Although I did face some isolation by breaking a gender norm, my experience was very different from other women that came before me.  When women in the late 1800s did something against the gender rules that society had set for them, they were completely outcasted from society or would face major punishments.  I use this example to show that there are still gender norms that need to be defied in today’s society to improve equality, but I also want to shed light on the fact that my experience in defying gender norms is vastly less consequential than those of the women of the late 1800s. 
Although I have focused mainly on women defying gender roles in this paper, men also face scrutiny when they defy gender roles.  Similarly to women, the intensity of the criticism men face in today’s world seems to be less than in the past.  For example, when boys would do cheerleading in the 1980s-90s they would be ridiculed for doing something that was “only for girls.”  They would be accused of being “gay” for doing cheer because they were acting too feminine.  They would also be told that they were only doing cheerleading because they were too weak to play a “real sport.”  The boys that did cheerleading would face a lot of hate because of the hegemonic masculinity that was ingrained in so many people.  The fact that these boys were doing gender in a different way resulted in so much pushback.  I have been involved in cheerleading for most of my life and I have seen how these criticisms that men face when they come into the sport have evolved.  I have had several male coaches that cheered during the time where they were teased for cheerleading but have told me that overtime as more people learn about cheerleading and as it grows in popularity, society has started to change their perspective. I definitely believe some people face more scrutiny when they come into cheerleading, depending on the open-mindedness of their community, but overall, I think society has come to more widely accept male cheerleaders.  Over time, as people become more educated, they are able to grow and come to realize that their perceptions of others should be made based on the individual, not the generalization that society has created for a specific group of people. 
Defying gender roles or norms that are harmful is important for the growth of society.
People should not have to alter their natural behavior and interests to fit into society’s box that defines how they should act based on their sex.  Defying gender norms and doing gender in your own way can be seen as an ongoing accomplishment as described by Candance West and Don H. Zimmerman in their article “Doing Gender” since it has the ability to alter society.  In the past, women worked to defy gender norms to gain their human rights.  Society has also shifted to become more accepting of men participating in activities previously deemed feminine.  In today’s world, society has become more accepting of people defying gender norms because they are becoming more aware that gender is something we have learned and do each day, not something we are hardwired to do. Categorical exclusion is the immediate or automatic rejection of the black applicant in favor of a white candidate. Shifting standards is described as evaluation being actively shaped or constructed through a racial lens. Lastly, race-coded job channeling is a process by which minority applicants are steered toward particular job types. This research study in whole showed that racial discrimination is still so prominent in todays world.

The Conception of Self Perception
	How we as humans perceive ourselves is a very interesting concept. Have you ever wondered why you or a given entity will act a certain way in accordance to the environment of that said entity? Likewise, have you wondered how different social interactions can affect the way you would consider yourself to “normally behave”. There are numerous reasons and scenarios that could influence one’s behavior. Multiple sociologists have put their minds to the cause and through a broader view of the “Self” they have touched on the conception of self perception. It is through their writings and ideals that we will dissect how we as humans view ourselves and in some cases why we change ourselves and our behaviors to appropriately fit the occasion.
	The idea of conception of self perception is simply formulating an idea of how we view ourselves.  We then get an idea of the reasoning behind our actions through looking at concepts provided by sociologists,  psychologists, and looking at examples of social interactions. There is an embedded system in our neurological working that self-consciously tells us how we should act, react, and where to place ourselves socially in a group. However, I am essentially challenging the idea that humans are in complete control over their actions and reactions. But, “How can anything other than the way I perceive myself, be the real me? Who is more me than me?” You are you, however, it is through a system of selves and social shields for certain situations that the “really real you” has manifested its residing. Perhaps it is more correct to say that the pure self is not what put these selves in place, but that past experiences have developed a better social construct. Whether it is in the soul, heart, or brain there is a pure self that defines who we are. The decisions we make in social interaction are affected by past experiences from which the pure self has learned and will integrate over time. At the end of the day the “you” that you perceive as “you” is only a part of the overall self that has been developed to fit a social interaction. So how does this occur?
	George Herbert Mead is a sociologist who uses the idea of the different selves to emphasize  his own idea of the “I” and the “Me”. He explains the selves as essentially being the different “you’s” you have for social situations. He demonstrates this idea when he says, “We carry out a whole series of different relationships to different people. We are one thing to one man and another thing to another… We divide ourselves up in all sorts of different ways with reference to our acquaintances. We discuss politics with one and religion with another. There are all sorts of different selves answering to all sorts of different social reactions.”, (Mead, 164). In this way, there are multiple parts to the self. Those parts make up what is referred to as the pure self, and these selves allow us to think of ourselves in whatever way we want to perceive ourselves in social situations. Think of it like this: one will act accordingly in the given environment. One doesn't act the same going in for a job interview as for a family Christmas get-together.  This is because the self has evolved from previous experiences. Accordingly, we know when to be more professional with our actions and when it is ok to be more laid back. It is because of this fact that the “you”, as you perceive yourself, is not what is in control of your social interactions. In fact a form of the pure self known as the social self is in control and is what drives us to act a certain way. The social self is the identity gifted upon an individual from the reactions of others, giving birth to social tendencies as an individual. Through this we learn what is and is not appropriate in a social situation. This is also why those who have more experience with social interactions are less socially awkward than those who have not learned from the social self. The social self is just one example of the different “selves'' that make up the pure self; however, it is the self most responsible as to why we react the way we do during social interactions.
	Despite the acceptance of the different selves that give insight into social interactions, there remains a belief that “I am as a human in control of my actions”. Essentially, the disbelief in the driving self provided through learned experiences. This type of logic is somewhat narrow minded. For example, when something scary happens the natural tendency is to run away. What triggered the tendency to run? The more narrow minded person would say, “I ran away because I wanted to get away from the scary thing, because I wanted to”. The sociological answer attributes the response to “fight or flight”, a response brought about from the parasympathetic nervous system when we perceive something to be dangerous. The key word here is “perceive”. The self told you it would be best to run from the unknown thing because past experiences have conditioned you to perceive the thing as scary. The reason the idea of humans being in absolute control of their actions/reactions is improbable is because nobody lives in a vacuum from reality. In other words, the idea suggests someone who has no knowledge of human interaction would react the same as someone who has grown up in society. To put this in perspective let’s look at two scenarios. Two children grow up differently, one child is in a fruitful middle class family home. This child loves Mickey Mouse, his parents get him Mickey Mouse themed merchandise, he watches the movies, etc. The child grows up seeing Mickey Mouse as a child friendly idol. In contrast, the other child is isolated from society living his whole existence in a box with no stimulation from anything or anyone. What if one day both the isolated child and the family child are surprised with their arrival at Disney World? The family child is blindfolded  and the isolated child is in his box upon entrance to the Magic Kingdom. What happens when the outside world is revealed and there stands Mickey Mouse? Isn't the answer ridiculously obvious? The child who grew up knowing Mickey Mouse would  be excited while the isolated child would shrink back into his  only known world that is the box from fright of this freaky human sized animalistic being. No matter what you believe is true, this is basically the outcome that would happen. Sociological belief would predict this outcome. The family child knew who Mickey Mouse was. He was taught through experience that Mickey Mouse is his friend. The isolated child never heard of Mickey Mouse so he was frightened by the unknown and would attempt to run and hide. However, the belief in the idea that humans are in complete control and social background has nothing to do with their reactions presumes the two children should react the same. According to this reasoning, past experiences are not reflected in “in the moment” decisions which is the flaw in this type of thinking. The two children in this scenario would undoubtedly not have the same reaction.
	The obvious question is, “why?”. “Why does our environment and background affect our behaviors? Why do we feel compelled to act a certain way when faced with certain situations?” There are a few concepts that can answer this question, and they are all rooted in self-perception. The way we view ourselves is a driving factor in how we present ourselves. There are essentially three ways of viewing yourself: there is how you directly view yourself, how others view you, and how you perceive others to view you. To put this in perspective, for a moment pretend You are a 10 year old child. You race your mom and she lets you win without you realizing it. She comments, “wow baby you’re so fast!” This starts to make you think you must be the fastest person in the world and this is how you view yourself. From your mom’s perspective, of course, she knows she let you win and you are most definitely not the fastest person in the world, this is someone else’s perspective of you. However, due to the fact you can’t read minds you have no idea this is the true perspective. All you know is that you left your mom in the dust and she is very impressed with you. This is your perspective of how you think others perceive you. Self perception is a powerful influencer on how to present yourself. As stated earlier humans are unable to read minds so we are only going to focus on self perception of yourself, through your own eyes and how you think others perceive you. 
    Firstly, self-perception through your own eyes is the subject of William James, a psychologist who uses sociological ideas to explain how we perceive ourselves. James describes the breakdown of the “self” into three key parts that help relate how you see yourself. James says the self is broken down into the social self, spiritual self, and material self. In short summary, the spiritual self is the personality, the social self is you defined in a social situation, and the material self is you expanding the self onto inanimate objects such as clothes, or a soccer ball. (For example, when you score a goal you say “I made it in!” when really the soccer ball made it in). James’ describes the idea of the self as, “We see then that we are dealing with a fluctuating material; the same object being sometimes treated as part of me, at other times as simply mine, and then again as if I had nothing to do with it at all. In its widest possible sense however, a man’s Self is the sum total of all that he CAN call his, not only his body and his psychic powers but his clothes and his house, his wife… All these things give him the same emotions. If they wax and prosper, he feels triumphant; if they dwindle and die away, he feels cast down-not necessarily in the same degree for each thing. Understand the Self in the widest sense, we may begin dividing the history of it into three parts, relating respectively to:
1.Its constituents 
2. The feelings and emotions they arouse-- Self feelings;
3. The actions which they prompt-- Self-seeking and self-preservation”, (James, The Self and its Selves, 123). The constituents according to James are the material, spiritual, and social self, along with the pure ego (most closely relating to the soul). Through this we see that James’ breakdown of the self into its constituents is used to provide self perception in which the self occurs over a three-step process: stimuli is received through one of the constituents, it is transferred into the brain, and the product is produced as behavior. This is how perception of ourselves through our own eyes is made. However, perception of ourselves based on how we think others see us is a different process.
	Secondly, self perception based on how we think others see us, is uniquely explained by psychologist, Charles Horton Cooley. Cooley’s views are very sociological and emphasizes how we rely heavily on social acceptance when making a decision. A good example of this is the decision making process that happens when choosing an outfit to wear in public. For the most part, humans feel inclined to choose outfits that will yield compliments. When picking out an outfit many of us begin to fantasize about people saying “wow nice look today!”  The pride generated by such a compliment will in turn cause us to continue to choose outfits that we think others would enjoy rather than one that may not result in such credit. This excerpt from Cooley’s, “The Looking-Glass self” sums it up the best, “A self-idea of this sort seems to have three principal elements: the imagination of our appearance to the other person; the imagination of his judgment of that appearance; and some sort of self-feeling, such as pride or mortification. The comparison with a looking-glass hardly suggests the second element, the imagined judgment, which is quite essential. The thing that moves us to pride or shame is not the mere mechanical reflection of ourselves, but an imputed sentiment, the imagined effect of this reflection upon another’s mind. This is evident from the fact that the character and weight of that other, in whose mind we see ourselves, makes all the difference with our feeling, We are ashamed to seem evasive in the presence of a straightforward man, cowardly in the presence of a brave one, gross in the eyes of a refined one and so on. We always imagine and in imagining, share, the judgement of the other mind. A man will boast to one person of an action say some sharp transaction in trade--which he would be ashamed to own to another.” (Cooley, The Looking-Glass Self, 142) As evidenced in the excerpt Cooley’s ideals are heavily reliant on the idea of social interaction. Stating that our actions can be rooted back to how we think others might think of us. With the introduction of his idea of self perception Cooley also introduced a new sort of Self. This reinforces the idea that there are a series of selves that control our thinking when taking an action or making a decision.
	Through the minds of William James, and Charles Horton Cooley, we were able to see the two different self perceptions in action. It is by breaking down the self into three selves all accounting for “you” in different areas of sociality, and by introducing a new or different self that we should consider how others might perceive us. The concepts work together but also apart from each other to show that we as humans are not as decisive on our own as we may think. Regardless of what you might think of this philosophy, there is no doubt that at some point in the reading of this paper there was realization or a connection that was made. These concepts were formed from critical thinking of life experiences to better understand how our “selves” behave in situations. Perhaps after reading this idea new ideas have started to form. We are a forever evolving species. Our neurological network is always learning and improving.

	Digging deeper into labor in the fast-food industry, George Ritzer came up with the concept of McDonaldization. McDonaldization is the general overlook at how rationalization affected the food service industry. Companies like McDonalds found ways around human labor to make more profit while saving time and money. Industrialization played a huge role in this, especially with the use of mass factory production that cut down on the need to pay employees. Another aspect of McDonaldization is the way fast food chains have created a sufficient, cheap process in order to sell as many products in as much time as possible. Ever been to a fast food restaurant and gotten your food in under two minutes? This is thanks to the “Medialization” of fast food. Cheap products combined with cheap labor and profitable prices is the recipe for success for fast food businesses like McDonalds, Wendy’s, etc. 
	McDonaldization is a prime example of what Marx talks about in capitalism, especially referring to estranged labor. Because of the McDonaldization of the fast-food industry, employees’ labor became even less valuable to companies. Most fast-food establishments pay their workers minimum wage in exchange for their work, which is nowhere near the kind of profits the companies are making off of their product. An average McDonald’s makes around 2.7 million dollars per year. An average employee making $11/hour working 40 hours a week earns about 0.8% of that store’s profit. This is where Marx’s estranged labor comes in, because the product doesn’t belong to the working-class laborers, it belongs to the power elite companies and company owners who are profiting from their cheap labor. Because capitalism is such a foundational part of the American economy, estranged labor is never going to be done away with. It’s everywhere you look. Not just McDonaldization, but in all types of stores. The girl at the mall folding clothes in Urban Outfitters isn’t making profit off you buying their outrageously overpriced shirts. The factory workers for American Eagle sewing clothes together aren’t getting paid based on how many sweaters get sold. Estranged labor is all around us.

If this sounds outrageous, it is way more common than you may think. Since 1990, white applicants received 36% more callbacks from a job interview than black applicants, and 24% more than Latino applicants with the same level résumé (Quillian). There has been a racial bias in the hiring process for decades. People are turned down for jobs they are highly qualified for based on their racial background and upbringing. Determination of whether or not a person gets a job and the wage they make should not be based on the color of their skin.
	Race has been a determining factor in many different cases on whether someone gets a job or not, whether or not people want to admit that. It also plays a factor in how much money they make from a job compared to their white coworkers. In a study done by Jud and Walker, a survey was conducted on 1,215 blue-collared males aged 18-28—consisting of 1,001 whites and 214 blacks—looking at their IQ, schooling, and earnings. The results were separated into low-social status and high-social status categories and then into black and white subcategories. The social status was based on the father’s occupation and Duncan Index, where it was showed if they made the average or less than the score for their job, they were placed into the low-social status category. Schooling had a big impact on the earnings the person made, which was lower in the black low-social status community where they began to be discriminated. Work experience was another impact on the individuals earnings, where blacks again were at a loss because they tend to have less work experience than their white competitors. The discrimination shines through when it was shown that low-social status blacks made $1,159 less than the low-social status whites on average. This shows that people of color with the same credentials as whites still make less money, based on their skin color. If discrimination was eliminated, black earnings could boost over twenty-five percent (Jud and Walker). The study explained above highlights the idea that racial discrimination is still a very real thing and that it can determine the amount of money someone gets paid for the same job as someone that is white in the same social class. If an individual is hard-working and gets their job done correctly, there should be no reason some make more than others. Discrimination in the workplace could easily be eliminated and it would allow for equality between races.

Inner cities tend to have a bad reputation, being seen as a place of widespread poverty, drug use, crime, etc. but not every person who lives in these areas represents that stereotype. Employers may see a person is from a bad area and assume they will be a poor worker or will act out in an inappropriate way, while this is not always the case, but if it was true, it could be because of the lack of work experience the individuals have due to the discrimination they face day-to-day. In a study done by Neckerman and Kirschnman, they observed interviews conducted on Chicago employers and the tactics they use in their interviewing processes. They focused on three areas while looking into the employer’s strategies: selective recruitment, job interviews, and employment tests. Selective recruitment is the idea of looking for certain types of people that meet their standards and could be based on “statistical discrimination” or race to predict the characteristics of the person they would be interviewing. Due to this process of selective recruitment, black and Hispanic applicants tend to have less of a chance, based on the bias that is present in today’s world that they may not be a good worker. Social class and where someone resides may also impact their chance of getting a job, because those who live in low-income areas have a bad reputation, whether or not they live up to that reputation. Job interviews conducted by a white male on a black male tend to be more prejudiced based on the fact they may not have much in common and race plays a role in the characteristics a person might have. Social cues and mannerisms impact a job interview as well, such as looking at a person’s posture, eye contact, or voice articulation. Black applicants tended to score lower on that scare, partly due to the difference in education or experience they have had. Prejudice and discrimination are seen amongst different races because they may not have been through similar experiences that they can comfortably have a conversation about, so in a job interview this makes it difficult to have an easy-flowing time. A skill test would allow everyone to have the same chance at the job since every individual is capable to complete the same tasks. Not all employers implicate employment tests and rely on selective recruitment or the job interview, which again discriminates racially due to the fact people of color are already at a disadvantage. The study found that most employers did selectively recruit by projecting their interviews in big neighborhoods outside of inner cities. The stereotype that is held over a certain race plays a big role in their chance of getting employed, which is not fair due to the fact not every person is the same. Those who come from a “rougher” background are given less opportunities to show their worth because they are discriminated against from a young age. Just because someone comes from a broken home does not mean they will create one, in a lot of cases it motivates the person to do good in the world and strive for greatness. Job interviewers and employers tend to look over that and look purely based on their backgrounds. Another thing that employers look for is job experience and because of that, many blacks do not stand a chance due to their lack of opportunities to find work experience.

Stewart and Perlow explore the idea of racial discrimination within the workplace and show how unfair it really is to people of color. 
Certain jobs have more employees of a certain race, so it makes it difficult for others to get hired. If a black male applied for a job that is typically ran by whites, they get turned down more often than not. Evaluator’s attitudes towards blacks tend to be fogged by the stereotypes that come along with the race, meaning they may rate their qualifications lower than those of a white person purely based on the reputation their race holds in society (Stewart and Perlow). How Beauty Standards Are Killing Women from Within
	Have you ever found yourself envying an attractive actress? It’s nothing to be embarrassed about, it is a common emotion when faced with popular actresses who are stunningly beautiful and live these glamorous lives. However, I guarantee I can describe the character’s general appearance. She probably had flawless skin, a flat stomach, large breasts, and a small waist that tapers out into a larger buttock region, yet her legs are thin enough to leave a gap between her thighs. Was I close? Predicting to physical features of a common actress or celebrity is not as difficult as you think in the age that we live in. In a time that is supposedly accepting of all people no matter their size, shape, ethnicity, religion, sexual orientation, or any other factor that makes them unique among others, there remains an underlying standard for women’s beauty that becomes increasingly more complex as the world of social media expands. Society claims to be increasingly concerned with the health of our bodies yet continues to objectify and judge women based on their physical features, which leads to all kinds of health issues including depression, anxiety, body dysmorphia, and eating disorders. 
	The topic of beauty standards and mental health is not a new topic to society, but rather one that has become increasingly more popular as our society transitions into the era of “Postmodern Beauty.” This new era is incredibly detrimental to the development of the personality, self-image, and overall mental of women of all ages. As a woman myself, I have seen and experienced firsthand these starling effects and I am frustrated at the fact that I have no choice but to mature in a culture that is based on uniformity. As children, we see each other as equals, with no real awareness of the shape and size of our bodies. We are fascinated with what the world has to offer and see our bodies as the simple vessels for life that they are. However, at some point, a switch is flipped, and you recognize that the orientation in which you present yourself is subject to the judgment of everyone around you. Some individuals gain great confidence or simply remain ignorant in acknowledging the judgment. For others, this is an all-consuming force that slowly chips away at their self-esteem and can cause catastrophic changes in their lives. 
	As a child growing up in rural Pennsylvania, I had little knowledge of social media and therefore was not aware of the standards to which I was supposed to conform to, however, I failed to recognize the nonelectronic influences around me. My parents did a wonderful job at raising my siblings and I to appreciate ourselves, nature, and all the experiences we had been blessed with. Although we protested for phones and other electronics our friends boasted about at school, they remained firm in shielding us from the inevitable detriment of these technologies. However, they could not hold off forever, so when each of us started our freshman year we got phones. I thought I was finally going to be able to make friends and be cool, popular, and all of the things that a 13-year-old valued. But I quickly found out that being close friends with my sibling and the way I dressed was “not cool” and my body measurements were considered “obese.” My spark of hope died out quickly as I listened more closely to the comments my “friends” made about my clothes, my personality, the way I spoke, my acne, and above all my body. Comments I had previously dismissed as jokes as I was oblivious to the harsh truth that being unique and experiencing normal bodily changes were ridiculed. 
In my first 2 months as a Freshman, I found my group of friends no longer talking to me, excluding me from group activities, and pictures, and making crude comments about my appearance behind my back. I began to regress from my social and outgoing nature. I threw myself into school and sports and became infatuated with social media and what was acceptable. I stopped eating breakfast and what little food I ate for lunch I ate alone in my English teacher’s classroom to avoid judgment. I became consumed with the looks I got in the hallways and overanalyzed every conversation I had throughout my day trying to figure out if I looked how they wanted me to. By the beginning of my sophomore year, I had lost almost fifty pounds and I was constantly tired and hungry. People commended me for my weight loss, but it still wasn’t enough to get back the friendships I had lost. Then the pandemic hit. Suddenly no one saw me every day, I couldn’t bury my thoughts in school or athletics because everything was shut down. I was left alone with my thoughts, social media, and most importantly my family. In such a constructive environment I began to dig myself out of the hole of my negative self-image and pulled away from the harsh environment of social media. I gained back some of my weight in muscle and became more comfortable being alone with myself and accepting my uniqueness. 
Society is structured with the façade of encouraging each and everyone to be different yet is only truly accepting of those who fit the mold of “perfection.” Although I was able to heal from such a dark time in my life I still deal with constant anxiety and self-esteem issues that will never really go away as long as I live presently in our society. I have seen this need to conform in many other women in my life as well. I have spoken to peers who have spent hundreds of dollars on lip fillers at 17 years old and more recently a friend expressed her excitement as her breast enhancement surgery was just scheduled for the upcoming month, she is only nineteen. Women are constantly striving to attain the perfect body encouraged by multiple factors in American society from influencers such as the Kardashians to weight loss supplement advertisements to the simple plastic doll known as Barbie. These “health” and “beautiful” bodies are riddled with unrealistic measurements and the expectation that women have thin limbs and a flat stomach while also sporting curves in “all the right places” and large buttocks and breasts. Genetically this is nearly impossible and results in continued dissatisfaction in your own skin. Sometimes the need to fit in can become so powerful it prompts women to take drastic measures such as surgeries or diets that often end in eating disorders, worsened body dysmorphia, and festering mental health issues. 
I am drawn to the complexity of this topic, not only from personal experience and the fear of raising children in such a harsh society but also from the elaborate take Naomi Wolf presents in her piece “The Beauty Myth.” Wolf defines the beauty myth itself as a commodified, censored, and unreachable physical ideal to which women must adhere. In other words, it is the idea that women should present themselves in a beautiful way while men should always have access to these beautiful women. This myth functions as a means of controlling the actions and appearances of women and keeping them under the control of society. It is a despicable idea rooted in the ideas of eating disorders, inferiority, and domestic violence, each of which is incredibly toxic in the grand scheme of how women see themselves. While Wolf claims the myth of beauty is an order that dictates behavior rather than appearances, it is clear that the behavior provoked produces actions contributing to the beautification or enhancement of the appearance of the affected individual. An example of this myth in effect was seen after the Industrial Revolution. As women began to emerge from their stationary place in the home they infiltrated secondary education, legal rights, the circle of trade, and the liberal professions. Men sought a means to weaken them and given that they already gained physical control of themselves they imposed beauty standards to weaken them mentally, contracting the rise of feminism. While this was imposed by all of society, it was pushed heavily by males in order for them to remain in prominent positions and keep women complacent in their servitude to men. In our modern age, the beauty myth has shifted substantially in the sense of what is its main source of power and momentum.
	As Wolf outlined in her piece men played the largest role in imposing this idea of strict beauty standards on women, motivated by remaining in power above them. However, I believe in the 21st century men are not responsible for the mass imposition of standards on women. It is the collective effort of both men and women to oppress other women. Men still strive to stay ahead of women as per the age-old tale of gender supremacy. The complexity comes when you consider how women oppress each other. If you think about it, which gender is inherently obsessed with the action of gossiping, a process of speaking poorly about someone based on a judgment they have made? When women discuss other women more often than not, they are critiquing the way the woman at hand has presented herself to society, referring implicitly to her physical features. Women partake in the breaking down of one another for the same reason men do, to gain more power over the oppressed, and do so through many means from physical speech to social media to pushing diet culture through society. This makes it increasingly harder for women to escape this maltreatment as it approaches them from all angles, attesting to the chain reaction of anxiety depression, body dysmorphia, and eventually eating disorders that lead to larger medical issues. Somehow society has taken the nontangible idea of “beauty” and invested so much, attention, time, energy, and resources into it allowing it to manifest and effectively kill these women from the inside out through their own behaviors and call it “healthy.”  Men and women will always have an underlying imbalance in power, but it would be to unsensible the imbalance women create within their own gender group. 
	Upon reevaluating Wolf’s idea of “beauty myth” I am prompted to reflect on my time in high school. My “friends” gossiped about my clothes, my skin, and my weight for the purpose of putting themselves ahead of me socially and ensuring that I would not be able to infiltrate their group, all of whom fit the mold of the “Barbie Doll” figure. I altered the way I acted by restricting my eating to change my appearance in an attempt to win over their approval. I recognize now that men had nothing to do will the change in my behavior, they were solely provoked by the insecurity of other women fighting for their own spots in the small social environment of our high school. A simple change in the environment I spent my time in daily shifted my outlook on my body and image, reinforcing the idea that without the presence of societal pressure from others the beauty myth is nonexistent, or has no power over an individual. If we are really looking for someone to blame, we should blame ourselves because even those oppressed are guilty of oppressing others. Wolf does an excellent job outlining this fact throughout the rise of feminism to the 21st century, requiring only the elaboration of the reader’s own place in society to recognize this malicious pattern. 
Our society is extremely contradictory in expressing and acting on their values. We claim to be increasingly concerned with the health of our bodies yet continues to objectify and judge women based on their physical features, which leads to all kinds of health issues including depression, anxiety, body dysmorphia, and eating disorders. We produce diets, advertisements, influencers, and even toys that project the need for an unrealistic body type to truly be “beautiful” in American society. This means, for women, there is no true escape from these detrimental standards. I would like to end on a positive note of hope for a future free of oppressive standards but in honesty, there does not seem to be a way to shift a pattern of oppression that spans thousands of years and continues to reproduce itself in new ways as technology continues to advance. Peace and equality among gender would be ideal yet unrealistic, however, peace and support among women could go a long way in helping to ease the impact of this oppression, allowing for the cultivation of body positivity and positive self-esteem among all women.

The Stage
Looking at me, I would say to my parents I am talkative and goofy, to my close friends that I’ve known a while I am pretty sarcastic, new friends consider me funny, my teachers would categorize me as quiet and diligent, and people I am meeting for the first time would consider me extremely quiet and potentially shy. Why do I have so many facades and appearances? Why do I act in such opposing ways when around friends, strangers, teachers, and parents? I present myself to different people differently in any given situation. Why do we all choose to be a different character around these different groups of people and in various settings? 
	“All the world’s a stage,” according to Shakespeare and that’s so true. It is understandable why it is so difficult to get to know who people truly are and why they act the way they do. This is because we are all actors and life is our stage. In the application of “Presentation of Self,” a person is an actor / actress and their “act” is dependent on the situation and who is present.  We project the image that we want based on the specific setting. What we project is the image of ourselves that we want others to see. It may or may not be part of our “true” self. Our friends, family, teachers, anyone we meet are constantly looking and judging to see who we really are.  Who is the “true” Carly?
	Our roles are an important part of how we act. We have various roles as we go through each day. We have roles that are ascribed, these are roles that were chosen for us, such as daughter, female, Hispanic, adopted. Then we have roles that we have choses such as student and hopefully nurse. It is through the performance we give that we express ourselves within each of these roles. This plays a large part in our behaviors and interactions throughout the day. I do not act the same in the role as daughter as I do in the role as friend, acquaintance, or student.
	In front of my parents, I play the role of daughter. It is in the role that I am most likely my “true self”. This may be the one role that is at this time in my life, this easiest role to play. They are the only people that love me unconditionally. As such, I am not inclined to need to search for the appropriate character, the role comes naturally. I feel very comfortable, so I am able to just be myself. In front of them the performance is very limited. Would everyone agree that I’m being one hundred percent myself? Probably not. They would probably assume that I act a certain way to please my parents. To some extent they are correct. I won’t talk to them like I would talk to my friends, because there is a certain amount of respect that you owe to your parents. Other than the way I talk to them, I would say I am myself in front of them. Since I have been in front of them and have known them since before I could really “perform” one could argue that I am not performing. At an early age I learned that if I misbehaved in front of my parents, there would be trouble. Things were much better for me if I just waited until they turned their heads. It was at that early age that we were already beginning to learn how to “act” in front of our parents. The daughter role is the easiest of my roles.  
	For the years of my high school I had been basically living “re-runs” or syndicated television shows or living in the movie “Groundhog Day” when it comes to the roles I need to play. I was living with my parents and my sister and going to the same the school. So I played the roles of daughter, sister, close friend, not-so-close friend, and student on a daily basis. So, for those four years of high school, and most likely the three years of middle school as well, I did not have the need to make that many adjustments to the “acts”. It was a comfortable time. Now and then a new friend or situation would show up, but for the most part, things remained relatively constant. Thing took a dramatic shift when it was time to hit the road to Wilmington, NC. I had several “discussions” with my new roommate over Snapchat before it was move in day for college. Over the internet is hard to determine how you need to act, what character you need to play. As I moved my stuff into my room, my parents were with me, along with my roommate and her mom. Who was I to be? On one hand, I was Carly, the daughter; and on the other, I was not sure who I was because Snapchat was not very helpful. Now this is every actor / actress’s nightmare, it is like forgetting your lines. My problem was, I had no lines. I had no directions on who I needed to be. 
	Now, turn your attention to center stage, things take a sharp turn. I was walking to one of my first days of college classes. One of my friends in our group had just told a crazy story about something that happened to her in her senior year of high school. As we were all laughing hysterically, I reached the place that is to be the spot for my class. I am entering the stage playing the role of a classmate. Suddenly, my back was little bit straighter, and I ran my fingers through my hair. Quietly I entered the building and found my classroom. I opened the door as gently as possible to ensure no one heard me so they would not turn around. I slipped into my seat and opened my bookbag and pulled out my laptop, ready for class. I sat quietly waiting on my professor. During class, I tried not to make eye contact with the professor. When in class I am a student and that is my role. As such, my character is quiet, and my demeaner studious. I am meeting the expectations of the teachers. This drives much of my behavior. They have the expectations that students are here to learn, and that education is first on their list. Teachers tend to keep personalities out of their evaluation of students. As such, with my teachers, I remain quiet and scholarly, blending into the crowd.
	The role of close friend is harder for me. I act differently given each of the friends. I think this is when different sociological concepts come into play as well. I think that in front of each one I act differently because of how I originally presented myself. When I met each of them for the first time, I was at a different stage in life, so I acted differently in front of each of them. The type of performance they put on when I first met them also influenced how I acted. My one good friend I met in sixth grade, at this point in my life, I was still unsure about who I really was so my performance conveyed someone who was colder and more closed off because I didn’t want to be judged. Her performance at the time was similar, so we got along and never had any cases of mistaken identity. My other good friend I met junior year of high school, by this time I was more comfortable with who I was and was able to be more myself when meeting her. Our dynamics are different, but they both work because we know our roles and how to perform in front of each other.  
	When meeting new people I am definitely perceived as quiet and probably shy. With new people I am unsure of the role I am supposed to play, so until I watch them for a while and get a feel of their part. Once I get to know them and we become friends I become more open and my performance changes. With my newer friends, they perceive me as an easy going and funny person and for the most part accept me. However, I also know that there is a risk of falling out of acceptance. As such, with my friends, I am able to be funny, but because there is always that chance of additional judgement, I stay sarcastic; it keeps me in control. I am also nicer because that level of comfortable enough to jokingly be mean hasn’t been reached yet. There are always the possibilities of roles getting changed though. 
	With my parents, they love me and want the best for me. They don’t judge me and have unconditional love for me, but they perform in front of me, they aren’t their true selves because they have the role of being in charge. My parents keep me on my toes and hold me accountable for what I say and do. Without this performance though, there would be an imbalance in the relationship. 
	On social media it’s an entirely different story. Only the good parts of life are really shared on social media, I think people use it as a little bit of an escape. They like to look at the pretty things in life. This however is toxic because there is no immediate physical presence of anybody and people aren’t really invested in what’s happening with you. 
Everybody has a different role they play in different situations and these roles only work if the performers are able to recognize the different roles. For example, in a group of close friends I am sarcastic, at home I am talkative and goofy, and yet to my teachers quiet and diligent. This is due to my “presentation of self,” this is the idea that in the immediate presence of others, people put on a performance. How do you know who someone really is, when all you can do is examine appearance and current “role performance”?  In each setting you could find yourself putting on a different performance, being “a different person”.
When you are alone and when no one is around, the stage is gone. It is at this time that you jump off the stage. You can remove all the facades that you have had to carry around throughout the day. It is at that time that you take a deep breath and realize that you are you. Are you funny? Yes. Are you sarcastic? Yes. Are you goofy? Yes. Are you quite? Yes. Are you diligent in your studies? Yes. Are you shy? Yes. Are you an actress? Yes. You become all of those things. So, are you truly acting? Maybe, but these are all parts of what make up you. They are pieces of who you are when you are with others and in other situations.

The Role Religion Plays in Today’s Society
	Religion has been at the roots of society since human civilization was formed. Overtime religion has grown and transformed dramatically. There are estimated to be about 10,000 religions practiced worldwide. The most practiced religions are Christianity, Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, and Buddhism. Religion has allowed for many people to form a community within their society. Emil Durkheim explains in his piece “The Cultural Logic of Collective Representations” that religion was a crucial part of the formation of society and aided in the creation of the collective consciousness. Yuval Noah Harari touches on the function of religion in today’s society in his book 21 Lessons for the 21st Century. Harari highlights how religion does not play as much of an influential role in today’s society because of the great advancement made by the human race through technology and complex thinking. Although Durkheim and Harari have differing views on the role of religion, both sociologist’s points are pertinent. Durkheim’s beliefs are more relevant to the beginnings of society, while Harari’s beliefs are more relevant to today’s society. Religion was crucial in the formation of society, but it has now become more obsolete and not necessary for societies to operate.
	Emil Durkheim brought forth the idea of the collective consciousness to sociology. The collective consciousness can be defined as a set of shared beliefs, ideas, and moral attitudes that unify a society. It defines what is “good” and “bad” in a society as well as the kind of morality an individual must exude in the society. This shared belief is necessary to maintain moral order. Without it, society would not exist since everyone would have different ideas of how society was supposed to function. For example, one person could believe that hurting another person for personal gain is perfectly fine, while another could believe that hurting another person in any aspect is very wrong. Without a consensus and agreement between the people, everyone would have different moral codes leading to major conflict and a community would be unable to form. Collective consciousness forms by humans interacting with each other in some pattern. The religious rituals that were performed by early civilization – which is a coordinated sequence of events that relate to a higher power – brought the community together because they were coming together for a common purpose. This common purpose could be a range of things whether it be to have good crops in the next season or to grant good health among all of the people in the community. Participating in these rituals facilitated communication and social gathering. These rituals allowed for collective life to become tangible which aided in the development of the collective consciousness. Durkheim argues that when the collective life reaches an adequate amount of intensity, religious life is the direct consequence. Since religion plays such a critical role in the development of the collective consciousness, Durkheim also argues that the fundamental categories of thought, science, and social institutions have religious roots.
	Yuval Noah Harari has quite a different take on the role of religion in society. Harari’s book 21 Lessons for the 21st Century focuses much more on religion in today’s world unlike Durkheim’s piece which focuses more on the birth of society. Harari argues the fact that religion has become less relevant to society’s function since human’s have advanced so much. Today’s society has integrated so much technology and science into people’s lives. With this advancement, people are exposed to much more information and scientifically supported explanations for things that may have previously only been explained by religion. With access to this information, people have the option to believe in the new discoveries or in the religious explanation. They are not limited to having to blindly believe in what religion says because it is the only explanation that society has been able to come up with. For example, religion used to tell people that sacrifices were the only way to have a good rain season and a good harvest, but now society has discovered the science needed to keep crops alive so that sacrifices are deemed unnecessary. Also, as the human race has grown, more religions have been born with different beliefs. These religions help bring together regions of people but having different religious beliefs has also led to many conflicts in the modern day. According to Harari, the entire human race is the society and having many religions does not help unify the community, but often polarizes people. Harari also refers to categories of issues that the world faces today including a technical aspect and a policy aspect. The technical aspect refers to the way things are done in the world and the policy aspect refers to how governments create policy to address problems in the world. Harari uses the example that if Egypt was struck by a plague of locusts, they could pray to Allah, but they would also call upon scientists to develop stronger pesticides and insect resisting wheat strains. In this situation, religion can play a role in the solution but modern-day solutions through science are also utilized. Harari also uses an example where he states that if a crucial decision needs to be made about the Iranian government, they turn to the modern scientists of economics to get answers because the 7th century Arabs did not have knowledge about modern economics that they could’ve put in the Quran. After coming to a solution using the ideas of Karl Marx, Milton Freidman, and Fredrich Hayek, they would also use a Quranic verse to support the economic decision. Here, Harari is trying to point out that religion is no longer the best or only way to make decisions since there are other resources for people to utilize. 
Durkheim and Harari have different views on the importance of religion in our society, but both sociologists have convincing points for their arguments. Durkheim believes that religion is what founded society and allowed for people to come together and form the collective consciousness. He argues that a society would not be possible without religion. On the complete other end of the spectrum, Harari believes that religion is not necessary for our society to function. Since the world has made such advancements in science and critical thinking, religion is not the only thing governing how or what people think. Despite the fact that both of these arguments are very different, they are both still valid and they can also be tied together. Religion was necessary for society to be born because it brought people together and allowed for them to form a collective consciousness. Without this collective consciousness, people would not be able to live in harmony together or have universal standard morals. Early civilizations used religion as a way to explain things that they could not explain on their own. They also used religion as a comfort for the unknown. Many fear the uncertainty and unknowingness of death, but the belief of going to heaven puts them at ease and makes it less scary. This is still present in today’s world. Science and technology have not been able to figure out what happens to one’s soul once they die, so religion is used as a way to explain it. Although, science and technology have been able to provide evidence for other instances where religion was used to explain the unknown. In today’s society, technological advancement has allowed for more information to be discovered. When new information is discovered, it disproves previous beliefs, like those that are embedded within religion. As new ideas are brought into the world and challenges religion, it also can create conflict. The same can occur between different religions who have different beliefs. Religion in today’s world can definitely bring forth conflicts, but it can also bring a sense of community and identity to people. Interacting with people who believe in the same things you do, helps solidify and reassure your ideas and gives you a community of people that you can turn to. Harari and Durkheim both touch on this topic. Durkheim’s views reflect how religion effected society when it was created, but Harari’s views reflect how religion does not affect society nearly as much in today’s society. 
Religion has majorly influenced our society in the way that it functions and the understood universal moral code. According to Durkheim, religion allowed people to come together because of a common belief which then resulted in the formation of the collective consciousness. With the formation of the collective consciousness, a society had the ability to form. As society has advanced through science, technology, and more complex thoughts and ideas, the role of religion has shifted. According to Harari, religion does not play as critical of a role in the function of society because people can rely on science and technology to give them explanations for things instead of religion. Religion can still be used today as something that someone can identify and feel a sense of community, but religion is not necessary for the functionality of society today.

The Looking Glass Self and Me
I overheard my parents complaining about me to one another, friends, and other family all the time. My siblings and I always joked about how our house had “rice paper” walls. Let me tell you, nothing, and I mean nothing is more irritating than hearing your parents talk down about you. Letters came in the mail from schools and programs for troubled youth. I was constantly being punished for one thing or another. I was always to blame for any and everything. The “common denominator,” as I previously stated. Anytime me and any of my brothers bickered, my parents would automatically assume I was to blame. At school I was the teacher’s pet. Perfectly behaved. We had citizenship sticker charts and I had the most stickers in my class. I was always on the honor roll and my teachers could not seem to praise me enough. The first “principle element” of the Looking Glass Self is the “Imagination of our appearance to the other person.” My parents left very little up to imagination. I knew exactly how they viewed me when private conversations were very loudly spoken just a room over (New York Italians do not know how to be quiet). My countless number of nicknames referring to my attitude problem very much reinforced the things I overheard. The many positive reinforcements for my behavior and the special treatment I received from teachers really solidified the idea that they believed I was good. I was viewed as two different children at home and at school. 
	The third and final principle is the presentation of yourself for others based on how you believe and imagine someone sees you.  Because I had conflicting views as to how others viewed me, I had two ‘presentations” so to speak. Based on my parents' negative view, I acted negatively.  I was the problem child. I acted out. I argued, fought, yelled, screamed, and threw fits. I was a terror. Any chance I had to cop an attitude, I did. Nobody needed to provoke me. I was a horrible listener, disrespectful, and mean. My attitude was “if they think that was bad, I’ll show them bad.” Every adult other than my parents thought of me positively. I was the golden child. So, at school, or at a friend's house I was perfect... A good listener, respectful, and well mannered. I was more than happy to lend a helping hand, sometimes without being asked. Know Your Audience
	Similarly to James, Erving Goffman theorized the idea of “The Presentation of the Self”, which essentially compared personality to a stage. He claimed that your “front stage” is your façade, while your “back stage” was composed of your true, raw self, unfiltered. In your “backstage” is where you prepared your presentation for your “front stage”, which is what the world would see. For example, when you are out at a bar with your friends, your “backstage” prepares your fun, silly, energetic part of your personality to put on your stage. However when you come home alone at the end of the night to your bed, you are your raw true self: “the backstage”. Goffman used the analogy of the stage to put emphasis on the fact that our brain is always putting on an “act”. He said that in no matter what social context, our backstage is always working to prepare the front stage to perfection.
	Interestingly, Goffman and James’ ideas have the capacity to go hand in hand. The “social self” is essentially a combination of the front and back stages. The back stage defines the role you are playing in the particular social context, while the front stage performs the different social self you must be playing. The idea of knowing your audience is especially important in both James and Goffman’s theories. Without social awareness, how could the backstage possibly know which social self to present on it’s stage? Without knowing the context of the musical, how can a marketer know which audience to target their show towards? An additional point in Goffman’s theory of the stage has been recently related to the use of social media. Current sociologists compare his theory to the idea that social media is also a stage—one who’s play never stops running. Your image is curated by your backstage in order to portray yourself how your followers want to see you. James would say that your defined role in social media determines the kind of content you are putting out for your followers. 
	Even though William James and Erving Goffman’s theories were multiple decades apart, their similarities are uncanny. Personality is a big component of both theories, especially the variations of personality that are portrayed throughout your day to day basis. James’ main idea about role identification in the social self directly correlates to the function of the backstage in Goffman’s theory of the stage. Essentially, the job of the backstage is to identify your role in context, so the front stage can present the appropriate version of the social self. Whether that be a loving, compassionate, helpful husband in the morning, or a strict, powerful, controlling boss during the work day, your backstage is always working to identify the role you are playing to put forth the correct identity.

Estranged Labor vs. Rationalization
While rationalization and estranged labor both touch on aspects of the human experience in today's capitalist society, they approach the subject from different angles. Rationalization studies the objective changes of social institutions that comply with logical principles, and estranged labor focuses on the individual's personal experience of alienation within the labor process. Despite these distinctions, both ideas provide insightful understandings of the difficulties and intricacies of modern socioeconomic systems.
There are similarities and differences when comparing rationalization and estranged labor. These ideas emphasize how people simply become parts of a huge, emotionless machine in today's capitalist society, which has the alienating consequence of destroying uniqueness. However, rationalization focuses more on the objective rearrangement of social processes and structures, while estranged labor highlights the subjective feeling of alienation among workers.
In addition, rationalization is frequently presented as having two sides, whereas estranged labor typically highlights the negative consequences of capitalist exploitation. While it does promote economic growth and technological advancement by bringing about previously unattainable levels of efficiency and organization, it can also result in the loss of deep personal relationships, the uniformity of culture, and a breakdown of established social institutions.
Imagine an assembly line setting in a modern manufacturing facility, where employees have been tasked with operating machinery to make consumer devices. During the day, every employee completes the same tedious tasks without interruption. Due to management's strict enforcement of result goals and quality standards, they have little control over the speed at which they work or the outcome.
Workers who experience estranged labor feel disconnected from the products of their labor, which they rarely see in their completed form. The completed devices are transported off to distribution locations without their input or recognition, which separates them from the rewards of their labors. Because they become little more than parts of production, the repetitive nature of their jobs creates a sense of boredom and disempowerment. A lasting sense of alienation may result from the employees' feeling more and more cut off from their jobs, their coworkers, and even their sense of purpose.
Rationalization principles guide the factory's operations. To simplify the assembly line, the production process is carefully planned, distributed among workers, and optimized for efficiency. Standard Operating Procedures are carefully followed to guarantee accuracy and reduce mistakes. Additionally, management uses data-driven research and performance metrics to satisfy market expectations and continuously enhance efficiency. Rationalization lowers costs and boosts output, but it also dehumanizes workers by treating them like interchangeable parts in the industrial process. 
The contrast between rationalization and estranged labor in this scenario highlights the complex structure of present-day industrial capitalism. Although rationalization promotes production and efficiency, it also makes workers feel more alienated, reflecting the deeper disputes that exist in capitalist systems between the needs of the economy and the well-being of people.
Both rationalization and estranged labor are useful lenses that view the processes that make up modern industrial capitalism, but they have advantages and disadvantages of their own. Marx's concept of estranged labor highlights the gap between people and the outcomes of their efforts and successfully portrays the subjective sense of alienation that workers feel inside capitalist institutions. 
However, Weber's idea of rationalization offers an organized structure for examining how social systems are reorganized in line with logical principles. It provides insightful information about how different aspects of society are rationalized. Rationalization has come under fire for putting efficiency and predictability ahead of human values and creativity, which has resulted in the alienation of the world and the collapse of established social systems. 
Rationalization and estranged labor reveal distinct aspects of a common phenomenon: the degrading effects of capitalism on people and communities. We can better understand the intricate details and mysteries present in current capitalist society and the urgent need for substitute models that put the well-being of people before achieving the goal of profitability by analyzing these ideas in unison.
